tury American architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:Aesthetics]]\n[[Category:American architecture writers]]\n[[Category:American designers]]\n[[Category:American diarists]]\n[[Category:American humanists]]\n[[Category:American industrial designers]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:American philosophers]]\n[[Category:American systems scientists]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:Bates College alumni]]\n[[Category:Black Mountain College faculty]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Auburn Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Critics of work and the work ethic]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Futurologists]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Independent scholars]]\n[[Category:Innovation economists]]\n[[Category:American inventors\u200e]]\n[[Category:Mensans]]\n[[Category:Milton Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Modernist architects]]\n[[Category:People from Milton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Penobscot County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of culture]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of economics]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of love]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of science]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of technology]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Gold Medal]]\n[[Category:Solar building designers]]\n[[Category:Southern Illinois University Carbondale faculty]]\n[[Category:Sustainability advocates]]\n[[Category:Utility]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Longisquama", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfluence and legacy:Fixed misspelling and added link to corresponding page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckminster_Fuller"}
{"title_page": "Korban", "text_new": "{{short description|Any of a variety of sacrificial offerings described and commanded in the Torah}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Qurbani]], a cognate word that refers to animal sacrifice in Islam}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Karbon (disambiguation)|Karbon]]}}\n{{redirect|Karban|the village in Iran|Karband}}\n{{Judaism}}\n{{Teshuva}}\n\nIn [[Judaism]], the '''korban''' ({{lang|he|\u05e7\u05b8\u05e8\u05b0\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05df}} ''qorb\u0101n''), also spelled '''''qorban''''' or '''''corban''''', is any of a variety of [[Sacrifice|sacrificial offerings]] described and commanded in the [[Torah]]. The plural form is '''korbanot.'''\n\nA korban was a [[kashrut|kosher]] [[animal sacrifice]], such as a [[bull]], [[sheep]], [[goat]],  or a [[dove]] that underwent ''[[shechita]]'' (Jewish ritual slaughter). Sacrifices could also consist of or include [[grain]], [[meal]], [[wine]], or [[incense]].<ref name=\"straightdope.com\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewsforjudaism.org/knowledge/articles/answers/jewish-polemics/texts/scriptural-studies/leviticus-1711/ |title=Leviticus 17:11 |author=Rabbi Michael Skobac |date= |website=Jews for Judaism |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330140559/http://jewsforjudaism.org/knowledge/articles/answers/jewish-polemics/texts/scriptural-studies/leviticus-1711/ |archive-date=30 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://beithamikdash.org.il/%D7%A7%D7%A8%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA/%D7%A2%D7%91%D7%95%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%A7%D7%95%D7%A8%D7%91%D7%9F |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150129185528/http://beithamikdash.org.il/\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea/\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea-\u05d4\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05df |archivedate=2015-01-29 }}</ref> Offerings were often cooked and most of it eaten by the offerer, with parts given to the [[Kohen]] priests and small parts burned on the [[altar (Bible)|altar]] of the [[Temple in Jerusalem]]. Only in special cases was all of the offering given only to God, such as in the case of the [[scapegoat]] and the [[Burnt offering (Judaism)|olah]] offering. <ref name=\"jewfaq.org\" /><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/2203-azazel |chapter=Azazel |author=Morris Jastrow |display-authors=etal |date=1906 |title= Jewish Encyclopedia|publisher= |access-date= 28 December 2018|quote=}}</ref> Common varieties of korban included the ''[[slaughter offering|zevah]]'' ({{lang|he|\u05d6\u05b6\u05d1\u05b7\u05d7}}), [[peace offering]], and ''[[Burnt offering (Judaism)|olah]]''.\n\nThe [[Hebrew Bible]] says that [[God]] commanded the [[Israelites]] to offer offerings and sacrifices on various altars. The sacrifices were only to be offered by the hands of the [[Kohen|Kohanim]]. Before building the [[Temple in Jerusalem]], when the Israelites were in the [[desert]], sacrifices were only to be offered in the [[Tabernacle]]. After the invasion of [[Canaan]], the main sacrificial centre was at [[Shiloh (biblical city)|Shiloh]], though sacrifice also took place at [[Beit Shemesh|Beth-Shemes]]<nowiki/>h,<ref>1 Samuel 6:14\u201315</ref> [[Mizpah in Benjamin|Mizpah]],<ref>1 Samuel 7:9</ref> Ramah,<ref>Samuel 7:17; 9:11\u201324</ref> and Gilgal,<ref>I Samuel 10:8; 11:15;13:9</ref> while family and clan sacrifices were commonplace<ref>1 Samuel\n16:2\u20135</ref> Under Saul the main center of sacrifice was Nob,<ref>1 Samuel 21:1 and the following verses.</ref> though private offerings continued to be made at Shiloh.<ref>2 Samuel 15:12</ref>  David created a new offering center in Jerusalem at the threshing floor of Arauna\u1e25,<ref>Also known as Ornan; 1 Chron. 21:23\u201326</ref> to which he moved the Ark.<ref>2 Samuel 6:17\u201318; 1 Chronicles 16:2, 40</ref><ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica | second edition | vol 17 | sacrifice | pg 645 | Anson Rainey</ref>  According to the Hebrew Bible, after the building of [[Solomon's Temple]], sacrifices were only to be carried out there.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=O'Day|first1=Gail R.|authorlink1=Gail R. O'Day|last2=Petersen|first2=David L.|authorlink2=David L. Petersen|title=Theological Bible Commentary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQWknj4ORJkC&pg=PA151|date=28 April 2009|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=978-1-61164-030-4}}</ref> After the Temple was destroyed, sacrifices were resumed when the [[Second Temple]] was built until it was also destroyed in 70 CE. After the destruction of the Second Temple sacrifices were prohibited because there was no longer a Temple, the only place allowed by [[halakha]] for sacrifices. Offering of sacrifices was briefly reinstated during the [[Jewish\u2013Roman wars]] of the second century CE and was continued in certain communities thereafter.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewfaq.org/qorbanot.htm |title=Qorbanot: Sacrifices and Offerings |last=Rich |first=Tracey R. |date=1998\u20132011 |website=Judaism 101 |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"straightdope.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/2091/why-do-jews-no-longer-sacrifice-animals |title=Why do Jews no longer sacrifice animals? |author=Straight Dope Science Advisory Board |date=17 April 2003 |website=The Straight Dope |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://the-tabernacle-place.com/articles/what_is_the_tabernacle |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427011353/http://the-tabernacle-place.com/articles/what_is_the_tabernacle |archive-date=2016-04-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhen [[sacrifice]]s were offered in ancient times, they were offered as a fulfillment of the [[613 commandments]]. Since there is no longer a Temple, modern religious [[Jews]] instead [[prayer|pray]] or give [[tzedakah]] instead to atone for their sins as the korbon would have accomplished.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Diamant|first=Anita|authorlink=Anita Diamant|title=Choosing a Jewish Life: A Handbook for People Converting to Judaism and for Their Family and Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=evEbFIza1c4C&pg=PT156|year=2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8052-1219-8}}</ref>\n\nThe practice and nature of sacrifices in [[Judaism]] are based on the 613 commandments, theology and ''halakha''. According to the Jewish perception the coming of the messiah will not remove the requirement to keep the 613 commandments.<ref name = \"Korn\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Jenson|first1=Robert W.|last2=Korn|first2=Eugene|authorlink2=Eugene Korn|title=Covenant and Hope: Christian and Jewish Reflections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-azoeVhNrcEC&pg=PA119|year=2012|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-6704-9}}</ref> Most [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jews]] believe that animal sacrifice will be resumed once the [[Third Temple]] is built, others believe that prayer and [[tzedakah]] will suffice.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n==Etymology==\n===''Qorban'' and ''qarab''===\nThe [[Semitic root]] {{smallcaps|\u221aqrb}} ({{lang|he|\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1}}) means \"be near\";<ref name=\"BotterweckRinggren2004\">{{cite book|author1=G. Johannes Botterweck|author2=Helmer Ringgren|author3=Heinz-Josef Fabry|title=Theological Dictionary of the Old Testament|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RAwg47G0M2IC&pg=PA136|date=9 January 2004|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-2337-3|page=136}}</ref> other words from the root include ''qarov'' \"close\" and ''qerovim'' \"relatives.\" The same stem is found in Hebrew and, for example, in the [[Akkadian language]] noun ''aqribtu'' \"act of offering.\" The Hebrew feminine noun ''korban'' (plural \u2018\u2019korbanot\u2019\u2019 {{lang|he|\u05e7\u05b8\u05e8\u05b0\u05d1\u05b3\u05bc\u05e0\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea}}) first occurs in the [[Bible]] in [[Book of Leviticus|Leviticus]] {{bibleref2-nb|Leviticus|1:2|HE}} and occurs 80 times in the [[Masoretic Text]]; 40 times in Leviticus, 38 in [[Book of Numbers|Numbers]] and 2 in [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]]. The related form ''qurban'' appears only in the [[Book of Nehemiah]] {{bibleref2-nb|Nehemiah|10:35|HE}} and {{bibleref2-nb|Nehemiah|13:31|HE}} \"wood offering.\" Traditionally the etymology is from the verb stem ''qarab'' and indicates the purpose to bring man close to God.<ref>Solomon Schechter in ''Understanding rabbinic Judaism, from Talmudic to modern times'' ed. Jacob Neusner p229 \"Hence the injunction to bring a Korban (sacrifice) even in this case; the effect of the Korban, as its etymology (Karab) indicates, is to bring man back to God, or rather to facilitate this approach.\"</ref><ref>Judaism in biological perspective: biblical lore and Judaic practices Rick Goldberg - 2008 \"The traditional etymology of korban is of a valuable object \"brought near to God \" (through the sacrificial act).\"</ref>\n\nThe [[Septuagint]] generally translates the term in Greek as ''[[wikt:\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd|\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd]]'' \"gift\", ''[[wikt:\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1|\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1]]'' \"sacrifice\", or ''[[wikt: \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac|\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac]]'' \"offering up\". By the [[Second Temple period]], Hellenistic Jewish texts use korban specifically to mean a vow. The New Testament preserves korban once as a transliterated loan-word for a vow, once also a related noun, ''\u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c2'' \"[[temple treasury]]\", otherwise using ''\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd'', ''\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1'' or ''\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac'' and other terms drawn from the [[Septuagint]]. [[Josephus]] also generally uses other words for \"offering\" but uses ''korban'' for the vow of the Nazirites ([[Antiquities of the Jews]] 4:73 / 4,4,4) and cites [[Theophrastus]] as having cited a korban vow among the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrians]] (''[[Against Apion]]'' 1.167 / 1,22,4).<ref>S Zeitlin ''Korban'' The Jewish Quarterly Review, 1962 - JSTOR \"Josephus, in Against Apion, who endeavored to ... Greek world was acquainted with the Judaeans, wrote that, \"The laws of the Tyrians forbid men to swear foreign oaths, among which he [Theophrastus] enumerates some others and particularly that called korban, which oath ...\"</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nContrary to the view that korbanot in the [[Torah]] were for sins, their use was far more complex\u2014only [[sin offering|some korbanot]] were used to atone for unintentional sins, and these sacrifices only accompanied the important required core means of [[Atonement in Judaism|atonement]] to be ever considered legitimate. Besides this one exception, there were the overwhelming majority of other purposes for bringing korbanot, and the expiatory effect is often incidental, and is subject to significant limitations. Korbanot are brought purely for the purpose of communing with God and becoming closer to him. Also, they were brought for the purpose of expressing thanks, gratitude, and love to [[God in Judaism|God]].<ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary.org\">{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/qorbanot.html |title=Jewish Practices & Rituals: Sacrifices and Offerings (Karbanot) |last= |first= |date= |website=Jewish Virtual Library |publisher=AICE |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}\n</ref>\n\nFurther, the use of korbanot was circumscribed for certain types of sins. Sins in Judaism consist of different grades of severity:<ref name=\"JE.SIN\"/>\n* The lightest is the ''\u1e25e\u1e6d'', ''\u1e25a\u1e6d\u1e6da'ah'', or ''\u1e25a\u1e6d\u1e6dat''  (lit. \"fault,\" \"shortcoming,\" \"misstep\"), an infraction of a commandment committed in ignorance of the existence or meaning of that command.\n* The second kind is the ''awon'', a breach of a minor commandment committed with a full knowledge of the existence and nature of that commandment (''bemezid''). \n* The gravest kind is the ''pesha'' or ''mered'', a presumptuous and rebellious act against God. Its worst form is the ''resha'', such an act committed with a wicked intention.\nThese three terms are mentioned by the Psalmist (cvi. 6): \"We have sinned [''\u1e25a\u1e6da'nu''], . . . we have committed iniquity [''he-'ewinu''], we have done wickedly [''hirsha'nu]''\" (comp. I Kings viii. 47; Dan. ix. 5).<ref name=\"JE.SIN\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13761-sin|title=SIN - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n\nWith few exceptions, korbanot could only be used as a means of atoning for the first type of sin, that is sins committed in ignorance that the thing was a sin.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewfaq.org/qorbanot.htm|title=Judaism 101: Qorbanot: Sacrifices and Offerings|website=www.jewfaq.org}}</ref> In addition, korbanot have no expiating effect unless the person making the offering sincerely repents his or her actions before making the offering, and makes restitution to any person who was harmed by the violation.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org1\"/>\n\n==Hebrew Bible==\n[[File:High Priest Offering Sacrifice of a Goat.jpg|thumb|The High Priest offers the sacrifice of a goat]]\n[[File:High Priest Offering Incense on the Altar.jpg|thumb|The High Priest offers incense on the altar.]]\n\nOfferings are mentioned in the [[Book of Genesis]], but further outlined in the later four books of the Torah, including aspects of their origins and history.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carasik|first=Michael|title=\u05de\u05e7\u05e8\u05d0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea: Leviticus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Alx1rJsiDFAC|year=2009|publisher=Jewish Publication Society|isbn=978-0-8276-0897-9}}, page 3 \"The majority of Leviticus deals with the offerings: how they are to be made, by whom, and where, as well as the ancillary rules that go along ....\"</ref>\n\nOfferings were practiced in the [[Tabernacle]] and during the eras of [[Solomon's Temple]] and the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]] until the total destruction of [[Judea]], Jerusalem, and the Second Temple by the [[Roman Empire]] in 70 CE.<ref>Baruch A. Levine ''In the presence of the Lord: a study of cult and some cultic terms'' 1974   Page 99 \"The Bible gives evidence of two modes of sacrifice in ancient Israel: 1) Altar sacrifices, of which at least some part was consumed by the altar fire, or was burnt as incense, and 2) Offerings placed before the deity and ...\"</ref> Every regular weekday, [[Sabbath]], and many [[Jewish holidays]] had their own unique offerings.<ref>James E Smith ''The Pentateuch'' Page 392 2006 \"Leviticus 23 presents in chronological order a list of \"the Lord's appointed feasts. ... Special offerings were presented each day of the feast.\"</ref>\n\nThe priests performed the offerings first in the ancient [[tabernacle]] and then in the Temple.<ref>Henry W. Soltau ''The Tabernacle, the Priesthood, and the Offerings''- 1972</ref> The Hebrew Bible describes the [[Kohen|kohanim]] (hereditary priesthood) as descendants of [[Aaron]] who meet certain marital and ritual purity requirements.<ref>Martha Himmelfarb ''A kingdom of priests: ancestry and merit in ancient Judaism'' Page 5  2006 \"On the other hand, P and H, the priestly sources, grant the priesthood only to descendants of Aaron, Levi's great-grandson.\"</ref> The [[High Priest of Israel]] played a crucial role in this regard on [[Yom Kippur]], a day when multiple offerings were offered.<ref>Alfred Edersheim ''The Temple -- Its Ministry and Services'' \"The Duties of the High-priest  - Seven days before the Day of Atonement the high-priest left his own house in Jerusalem, and took up his abode in his chambers in the Temple.\"</ref>\n\n===Women and offerings===\nWomen were required to perform a number of offerings, including:{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n* The offerings following childbirth as described in the [[Book of Leviticus]], 12.\n* [[Thank offering]] and its accompanying [[gift offering|meal offering]] following recovery from illness or danger.\n* The [[Passover sacrifice]] on [[Passover]]. Women could offer the sacrifice and hold a [[Passover Seder]] themselves if they wished, even if married.\n* [[Sin offering]]s or [[guilt offering]]s in atonement for transgressions and unintentional errors.\n* Offerings relevant to fulfillment of, or transgression of, the [[Nazirite]] vow.\n* Offerings following cure from certain diseases and unusual bodily discharges.\n\nWomen could also voluntarily participate in a number of other offerings and rituals for which they were not obligated, including:{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n* [[First Fruits]] on the holiday of [[Shavuot]].\n* [[Temple tax]] - The half-[[shekel]] tax for Temple needs.\n* Voluntary offerings, [[peace offering]]s and a variety of other voluntary and donative offerings.\n* ''[[Semicha in sacrifices|Semicha]]'' (laying on hands) of sacrificial animals for sacrifices they were not required to perform (Berachot 19a).\n* Women could slaughter their sacrificial animals themselves if they wished.\n\n===In the Nevi'im===\nMany books of the [[Nevi'im]] section of the [[Hebrew Bible]] such as the [[Book of Isaiah]] and [[Book of Jeremiah]] spoke out against those Israelites who brought forth sacrifices but did not act in accord with the precepts of the Law. The Prophets disparaged sacrifices that were offered without a regeneration of the heart, i.e., a determined turning from sin and returning to God by striving after righteousness ([[Book of Hosea]] 14:1-2, Joel 2:13, Micah 6:6-8). At the same time, prophets stressed the importance of offerings combined with justice and good even as they taught that offerings were unacceptable unless combined with heartfelt repentance and good deeds. [[Malachi]], the last prophet in the Hebrew Bible, emphasized that the goal of repentance is not to end sacrifices, but to make the offerings fit for acceptance once again ([[Book of Malachi]], 3:3-4). Similarly, the [[Book of Isaiah]] despite disparagement of sacrifices without justice, portrays sacrifice as having a role complementary with prayer in a universalistic [[eschatology]] (Isaiah 56:1; 6-7).\n\n==Rabbinical interpretation==\n\n===100 among the 613 commandments===\nAccording to [[Maimonides]], about one hundred of the permanent [[613 commandments]] based on the Torah, by rabbinical enumeration, directly concern sacrifices, excluding those commandments that concern the actual Temple and the priests themselves of which there are about another fifty.<ref>\n# Not to burn anything on the Golden Altar besides incense (Exodus 30:9)\n# To offer only unblemished animals (Leviticus 22:21)\n# Not to dedicate a blemished animal for the altar (Leviticus 22:20)\n# Not to slaughter it (Leviticus 22:22)\n# Not to sprinkle its blood (Leviticus 22:24)\n# Not to burn its ''[[Chelev|khelev]]'' (Leviticus 22:22)\n# Not to offer a temporarily blemished animal (Deuteronomy 17:1)\n# Not to sacrifice blemished animals even if offered by non-Jews (Leviticus 22:25)\n# Not to inflict wounds upon dedicated animals (Leviticus 22:21)\n# To redeem dedicated animals which have become disqualified (Deuteronomy 12:15)\n# To offer only animals which are at least eight days old (Leviticus 22:27)\n# Not to offer animals bought with the wages of a harlot or the animal exchanged for a dog (Deuteronomy 23:19)\n# Not to burn honey or yeast on the altar (Leviticus 2:11)\n# To salt all sacrifices (Leviticus 2:13)\n# Not to omit the salt from sacrifices (Leviticus 2:13)\n# Carry out the procedure of the burnt offering as prescribed in the Torah (Leviticus 1:3)\n# Not to eat its meat (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# Carry out the procedure of the sin offering (Leviticus 6:18)\n# Not to eat the meat of the inner sin offering (Leviticus 6:23)\n# Not to decapitate a fowl brought as a sin offering (Leviticus 5:8)\n# Carry out the procedure of the guilt offering (Leviticus 7:1)\n# The ''kohanim'' must eat the sacrificial meat in the Temple (Exodus 29:33)\n# The ''kohanim'' must not eat the meat outside the Temple courtyard (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# A non-''kohen'' must not eat sacrificial meat (Exodus 29:33)\n# To follow the procedure of the peace offering (Leviticus 7:11)\n# Not to eat the meat of minor sacrifices before sprinkling the blood (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# To bring meal offerings as prescribed in the Torah (Leviticus 2:1)\n# Not to put oil on the meal offerings of wrongdoers (Leviticus 5:11)\n# Not to put frankincense on the meal offerings of wrongdoers (Leviticus 3:11)\n# Not to eat the meal offering of the High Priest (Leviticus 6:16)\n# Not to bake a meal offering as leavened bread (Leviticus 6:10)\n# The ''kohanim'' must eat the remains of the meal offerings (Leviticus 6:9)\n# To bring all avowed and freewill offerings to the Temple on the first subsequent festival (Deuteronomy 12:5-6)\n# To offer all sacrifices in the Temple (Deuteronomy 12:11)\n# To bring all sacrifices from outside Israel to the Temple (Deuteronomy 12:26)\n# Not to slaughter sacrifices outside the courtyard (of the Temple) (Leviticus 17:4)\n# Not to offer any sacrifices outside the courtyard (of the Temple) (Deuteronomy 12:13)\n# To offer two lambs every day (Numbers 28:3)\n# To light a fire on the altar every day (Leviticus 6:6)\n# Not to extinguish this fire (Leviticus 6:6)\n# To remove the ashes from the altar every day (Leviticus 6:3)\n# To burn incense every day (Exodus 30:7)\n# The ''Kohen Gadol'' must bring a meal offering every day (Leviticus 6:13)\n# To bring two additional lambs as burnt offerings on Shabbat (Numbers 28:9)\n# To bring additional offerings on the New Month (''[[Rosh Khodesh]]'') (Numbers 28:11)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Passover]] (Numbers 28:19)\n# To offer the wave offering from the meal of the new wheat (Leviticus 23:10)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Shavuot]] (Numbers 28:26)\n# To bring two leaves to accompany the above sacrifice (Leviticus 23:17)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Rosh Hashana]] (Numbers 29:2)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Yom Kippur]] (Numbers 29:8)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Sukkot]] (Numbers 29:13)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Shmini Atzeret]] (Numbers 29:35)\n# Not to eat sacrifices which have become unfit or blemished (Deuteronomy 14:3)\n# Not to eat from sacrifices offered with improper intentions (Leviticus 7:18)\n# Not to leave sacrifices past the time allowed for eating them (Leviticus 22:30)\n# Not to eat from that which was left over (Leviticus 19:8)\n# Not to eat from sacrifices which became impure (Leviticus 7:19)\n# An impure person must not eat from sacrifices (Leviticus 7:20)\n# To burn the leftover sacrifices (Leviticus 7:17)\n# To burn all impure sacrifices (Leviticus 7:19)\n# To follow the [sacrificial] procedure of Yom Kippur in the sequence prescribed in ''Parshah [[Acharei]] Mot'' (After the death of [[Aaron]]'s sons...) (Leviticus 16:3)\n# One who profaned property must repay what he profaned plus a fifth and bring a sacrifice (Leviticus 5:16)\n# Not to work consecrated animals (Deuteronomy 15:19)\n# Not to shear the fleece of consecrated animals (Deuteronomy 15:19)\n# To slaughter the paschal sacrifice at the specified time (Exodus 12:6)\n# Not to slaughter it while in possession of leaven (Exodus 23:18)\n# Not to leave the fat overnight (Exodus 23:18)\n# To slaughter the second Paschal lamb (Numbers 9:11)\n# To eat the [[Passover sacrifice]] with ''[[matzah]]'' and ''marror'' on the night of the 15th of Nissan (Exodus 12:8)\n# To eat the second Paschal Lamb on the night of the 15th of Iyar (Numbers 9:11)\n# Not to eat the Paschal meat raw or boiled (Exodus 12:9)\n# Not to take the Paschal meat from the confines of the group (Exodus 12:46)\n# An apostate must not eat from it (Exodus 12:43)\n# A permanent or temporary hired worker must not eat from it (Exodus 12:45)\n# An uncircumcised male must not eat from it (Exodus 12:48)\n# Not to break any bones from the paschal offering (Exodus 12:46)\n# Not to break any bones from the second paschal offering (Numbers 9:12)\n# Not to leave any meat from the Paschal offering over until morning (Exodus 12:10)\n# Not to leave the second Paschal meat over until morning (Numbers 9:12)\n# Not to leave the meat of the holiday offering of the 14th until the 16th (Deuteronomy 16:4)\n# To celebrate on  [[Passover]], [[Shavuot]], and [[Sukkot]] at the [[Temple of Solomon|Temple]] (bring a peace offering) (Exodus 23:14)\n# To rejoice on these three Festivals (bring a peace offering) (Deuteronomy 16:14)\n# Not to appear at the Temple without offerings (Deuteronomy 16:16)\n# Not to refrain from rejoicing with, and giving gifts to, the Levites (Deuteronomy 12:19)\n# The ''kohanim'' must not eat unblemished firstborn animals outside Jerusalem (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# Every person must bring a sin offering for his transgression (Leviticus 4:27)\n# Bring an ''asham talui'' when uncertain of guilt (Leviticus 5:17-18)\n# Bring an ''asham vadai'' when guilt is ascertained (Leviticus 5:25)\n# Bring an ''oleh v'yored'' offering (if the person is wealthy, an animal; if poor, a bird or meal offering) (Leviticus 5:7-11)\n# The [[Sanhedrin]] must bring an offering when it rules in error (Leviticus 4:13)\n# A woman who had a running issue (unnatural [[Menstrual cycle|menstrual]] flow) must bring an offering after she goes to the [[Mikveh|ritual bath]] (Leviticus 15:28-29)\n# A woman who gave birth must bring an offering after she goes to the bath (Leviticus 12:6)\n# A man who had a running issue (unnatural [[semen]] flow) must bring an offering after he goes to the bath (Leviticus 15:13-14)\n# A ''metzora'' (a person with ''[[tzaraas]]'')  must bring an offering after going to the [[Mikveh]] (Leviticus 14:10)\n# Not to substitute another beast for one set apart for sacrifice ([[temurah (Halacha)|temurah]]) (Leviticus 27:10)\n# The new animal, in addition to the substituted one, retains consecration (Leviticus 27:10)\n# Not to change consecrated animals from one type of offering to another (Leviticus 27:26)\n# Carry out the procedure of the [[red heifer]] (Numbers 19:2)\n# Carry out the laws of the sprinkling water (Numbers 19:21)\n# Break the neck of a calf by the river valley following an unsolved murder (Deuteronomy 21:4)</ref>\n\n===Instructions in Mishnah and Talmud===\nThe [[Mishnah]] and [[Talmud]] devote a very large section, known as a ''seder'', to the study and analysis of this subject known as ''[[Kodashim|Qodashim]]'', whereby all the detailed varieties of korbanot are enumerated and analyzed in great logical depth, such as ''qodshim kalim'' (\"of minor degree of sanctity\") and ''qodashei qodashim'' (\"of major degree of sanctity\"). In addition, large parts of every other book of the Talmud discuss various kinds of sacrifices. ''Pesachim'' is largely devoted to a discussion of how to offer the [[Passover sacrifice]]. ''Yoma'' contains a detailed discussion of the offerings and Temple ritual on Yom Kippur (Day of Atonement), and there are sections in ''seder Moed'' (Festivals) for the special offerings and Temple ritual for other major Jewish holidays. ''Sheqalim'' discusses the annual half-shekel offering for Temple maintenance and Temple governance and management, ''Nashim'' discusses the offerings made by [[Nazirite]]s and the suspected adultress, etc.\n\nThe Talmud provides extensive details not only on how to perform sacrifices but how to adjudicate difficult cases, such what to do if a mistake was made and whether improperly performing one of the required ritual elements invalidates it or not. The Talmud explains how to roast the Passover offering, how to dash blood from different kinds of sacrifices upon the altar, how to prepare the incense, the regulatory code for the system of taxation that financed the priesthood and public sacrifices, and numerous other details.\n\n===Rationale and rabbinic commentary===\n[[Maimonides]], a medieval Jewish scholar, drew on the early critiques of the need for sacrifice, taking the view that God always held sacrifice inferior to prayer and philosophical meditation. However, God understood that the Israelites were used to the animal sacrifices that the surrounding pagan tribes used as the primary way to commune with their gods. As such, in Maimonides' view, it was only natural that Israelites would believe that sacrifice would be a necessary part of the relationship between God and man. Maimonides concludes that God's decision to allow sacrifices was a concession to human psychological limitations. It would have been too much to have expected the Israelites to leap from pagan worship to prayer and meditation in one step. In ''[[The Guide for the Perplexed]]'', he writes:\n{{quote|But the custom which was in those days general among men, and the general mode of worship in which the Israelites were brought up consisted in sacrificing animals... It was in accordance with the wisdom and plan of God...that God did not command us to give up and to discontinue all these manners of service. For to obey such a commandment would have been contrary to the nature of man, who generally cleaves to that to which he is used; it would in those days have made the same impression as a prophet would make at present [the 12th Century] if he called us to the service of God and told us in His name, that we should not pray to God nor fast, nor seek His help in time of trouble; that we should serve Him in thought, and not by any action.<ref>Book III, Chapter 32. Translated by M. Friedlander, 1904, ''The Guide for the Perplexed'', Dover Publications, 1956 edition</ref>}}\n\nIn contrast, many others such as [[Nahmanides]] (in his commentary on Leviticus 1:9) disagreed. Nahmanides cites the fact that the Torah records the practices of animal and other sacrifices from the times of [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]] and earlier. Indeed, the purpose of recounting the [[Binding of Isaac|near sacrifice of Isaac]] was to illustrate the sublime significance and need of animal sacrifices as supplanting the abomination of human sacrifices.\n\n===In spiritual practice===\nThe korban also has a spiritual meaning, and refers to some part of an individual's ego, which is given up as a sacrifice to God in honor of the mortality of the worshipper. In keeping with the root of the word, meaning to draw close, and to the common usage as the sacrifice of an animal, so too can the worshipper sacrifice something of this world in order to become closer to God.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =  Dubov\n  | first =  Nissan Dovid \n  | title = Jewish Meditation\n  | publisher =Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center\n  | url = http://www.chabad.org/library/article.asp?AID=361886\n  | accessdate =  2006-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==The end of sacrifices==\nWith the destruction of the Second Temple in Jerusalem by the Romans, the Jewish practice of offering korbanot stopped for all intents and purposes. Despite subsequent intermittent periods of small Jewish groups offering the traditional sacrifices on the Temple Mount, the practice effectively ended.\n\n[[Rabbinic Judaism]] was forced to undergo a significant development in response to this change; no longer could Judaism revolve around the Temple services. The destruction of the Temple led to a development of Judaism in the direction of text study, prayer, and personal observance. [[Orthodox Judaism]] regards this as being largely an alternative way of fulfilling the obligations of the Temple. Other branches of Judaism ([[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]], [[Reform Judaism|Reform]], and [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]]) regard the korbanot as an ancient ritual that will not return. A range of responses is recorded in classical rabbinic literature, describing this subject.\n\n:Once, Rabbi Yohanan ben Zakkai was walking with his disciple, Rabbi Y'hoshua, near Jerusalem after the destruction of the Temple. Rabbi Y'hoshua looked at the Temple ruins and said \"Alas for us!! The place that atoned for the sins of the people Israel lies in ruins!\" Then Rabbi Yohannan ben Zakkai spoke to him these words of comfort:  'Be not grieved, my son. There is another equally meritorious way of gaining ritual atonement, even though the Temple is destroyed. We can still gain ritual atonement through deeds of loving-kindness. For it is written \"Loving kindness I desire, not sacrifice.\" (Hosea 6:6)\n:[[Midrash]] Avot D'Rabbi Nathan 4:5\n\nIn the [[Babylonian Talmud]], a number of sages opined that following Jewish law, doing charitable deeds, and studying Jewish texts is greater than performing animal sacrifices.\n\n:Rabbi Elazar said: Doing righteous deeds of charity is greater than offering all of the sacrifices, as it is written: \"Doing charity and justice is more desirable to the Lord than sacrifice\" (Proverbs 21:3).\n:Babylonian Talmud, Sukkah 49\n\nNonetheless, numerous texts of the Talmud stress the importance of and hope for eventual re-introduction of sacrifices, and regard their loss as a terrible tragedy. Partaking of sacrificial offerings was compared to eating directly at one's Father's table, whose loss synagogue worship does not quite entirely replace. One example is in ''Berachot'':\n:And I said to him: I heard a heavenly voice that was cooing like a dove and saying, \"Woe to the children because of whose sins I destroyed My house, and burned My temple, and exiled them among the nations of the world. And he [Elijah the prophet] said to me: \"By your life and the life of your head! It is not only at this moment that [the heavenly voice] says this. But on each and every day it says this three times. And not only this, but at the time that the people of Israel enter the synagogues and houses of study, and respond (in the [[Kaddish]]) \"May His great name be blessed\", the Holy One, Blessed is He, shakes His head and says: \"Fortunate for the king who is praised this way in his house. What is there for the Father who has exiled His children. And woe to the children who have been exiled from their Father's table.\"  (Talmud ''Berachot'' 3a).\n\nAnother example is in ''Sheqalim'':\n:Rabbi Akiva said: Shimon Ben Loga related the following to me: I was once collecting grasses, and I saw a child from the [[House of Avitnas]] (the incense-makers). And I saw that he cried, and I saw that he laughed. I said to him, \"My son, why did you cry?\" He said, Because of the glory of my Father's house that has decreased.\" I asked \"And why did you laugh?\" He said to me \"Because of the glory prepared for the righteous in the future.\" I asked \"And what did you see?\" [that brought on these emotions]. \"The herb ''[[Maaleh Ashan|maaleh ashan]]'' is growing next to me. [''Maaleh Ashan'' is the secret ingredient in the incense that made the smoke rise, which according to the Talmud the [[House of Avitnas]] never revealed.]\"\n\n===Liturgical attention to end of sacrifices===\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2016}}\nNumerous details of the daily religious practice of an ordinary Jew are connected to keeping memory of the rhythm of the life of the Temple and its sacrifices. For example, the Mishna begins with a statement that the [[Shema Yisrael]] prayer is to be recited in the evening at the time when Kohanim who were ''[[Tumah and taharah|tamei]]'' (ritually impure) are permitted to enter to eat their [[heave offering]] (a food-tithe given to priests) following purification. A detailed discussion of the obligations of tithing, ritual purity, and other elements central to the Temple and priesthood is required in order to determine the meaning of this contemporary daily Jewish obligation.\n\n===Other occasions===\nJewish services for [[Shabbat]], Jewish holidays and other occasions include special prayers for the restoration of sacrifices. For example, the traditional Yom Kippur liturgy contains repeated prayers for the restoration of sacrifices and every [[High Holiday]] [[Amidah]] contains [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 56:7:\n:Even them will I bring to My holy mountain, and make them joyful in My house of prayer; their burnt-offerings and their sacrifices shall be acceptable upon Mine altar; for My house shall be called a house of prayer for all peoples.<ref name=\"mechon-mamre.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mechon-mamre.org/p/pt/pt1056.htm|title=Isaiah 56 / Hebrew - English Bible / Mechon-Mamre|website=www.mechon-mamre.org}}</ref>\n\n==Modern view and resumption of sacrifices==\n\n===Future of sacrifices in Judaism===\n{{see also| Temple in Jerusalem}}\nThe prevailing belief among rabbinic Jews is that in the [[Messianic Age|messianic era]], the [[Messiah in Judaism|Messiah]] will come and a [[Third Temple]] will be built. It is believed that the korbanot will be reinstituted, but to what extent and for how long is unknown. Some biblical and classical rabbinic sources hold that most or all sacrifices will not need to be offered.\n\n* In the future all sacrifices, with the exception of the Thanksgiving-sacrifice, will be discontinued. (Midrash Vayikra Rabbah 9:7)\n* All sacrifices will be annulled in the future. (Tanchuma Emor 14, Vayikra Rabbah 9:7)\n* Then the grain-offering of Judah and Jerusalem will be pleasing to God as in the days of old, and as in ancient years. (Malachi 3:4)\n* It is impossible to go suddenly from one extreme to the other;...the custom which was in those days general among all men, and the general mode of worship in which the Israelites were brought up consisted of sacrificing animals in the temples... For this reason God allowed this kind of service to continue.  The sacrificial system is not the primary object, rather supplications, and prayer. (Maimonides, The Guide to the Perplexed III 32)\n\nThe majority view of classical rabbis is that the Torah's commandments will still be applicable and in force during the messianic era. However, a significant minority of rabbis held that most of the commandments will be nullified in the messianic era, thus holding that sacrifices will not be reinstated. Examples of such rabbinic views include:\n* Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Niddah 61b and Tractate Shabbat 151b.\n* Midrash Shochar Tov (Mizmor 146:5) states that God will permit what is now forbidden.\n\n[[Orthodox Judaism]] holds that in the messianic era, most or all of the korbanot will be reinstituted, at least for a time. [[Conservative Judaism]] and [[Reform Judaism]], hold that no animal sacrifices will be offered in a rebuilt Temple at all, following the position of Tanchuma Emor 14 and Vayikra Rabbah 9:7.\n\n===Nineteenth and twentieth century===\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2017}}\nIn the 1800s a number of Orthodox rabbis studied the idea of reinstating korbanot on the Temple Mount, even though the messianic era had not yet arrived and the Temple was not rebuilt. A number of [[responsa]] concluded that within certain parameters, it is permissible according to Jewish law to offer such sacrifices.\n\nDuring the early 20th century, [[Israel Meir Kagan]] advised some followers to set up special ''[[yeshiva]]s'' for married students known as ''Qodshim [[Kolel]]im'' that would specialize in the study of the korbanot and study with greater intensity the ''qodshim'' sections of the [[Talmud]] in order to prepare for the arrival of the Jewish Messiah who would oversee the rebuilding of the original Temple of Solomon in [[Jerusalem]] that would be known as the [[Third Temple]]. His advice was taken seriously and today there are a number of well-established [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] institutions in [[Israel]] that focus solely on the subject of the korbanot, ''qodshim'', and the needs of the future Jewish Temple, such as the [[Brisk tradition and Soloveitchik dynasty]].\n\n===Efforts to restore korbanot===\n{{Main|The Third Temple}}\nA few groups, notably the [[Temple Institute]] and the [[Temple Mount Faithful]], have petitioned the Israeli government to rebuild a Third Temple on the [[Temple Mount]] and restore sacrificial worship. The Israeli government has not responded favorably. Most Orthodox Jews regard rebuilding a Temple as an activity for a Jewish Messiah as part of a future [[Jewish eschatology]], and most non-Orthodox Jews do not believe in the restoration of sacrificial worship at all. The Temple Institute has been constructing ritual objects in preparation for a resumption of sacrifices.\n\n==View among modern Jewish denominations==\n\n===Contemporary Orthodox Judaism===\nToday Orthodox Judaism includes mention of each korban on either a daily basis in the ''[[siddur]]'' (daily prayer book), or in the ''[[machzor]]'' (holiday prayerbook) as part of the prayers for the relevant days concerned. They are also referred to in the prayerbooks of Conservative Judaism, in an abbreviated fashion.\n\nOn each Jewish holiday the sections in the Torah mentioning that festival's korbanot is read out loud in [[synagogue]].\n\n====Daily services====\nIn the very early morning daily ''[[Shacharit]]'' prayers for example, they include the following in order of mention, actually called the korbanot. The following example is taken from the [[Nusach Ashkenaz]].\n* ''Kiyor'' Describing the basin containing pure water to wash up before touching the korbanot (offerings), based on Exodus 30: 17-21.<ref name=\"bible.ort.org\">http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=2&CHAPTER=30</ref>\n* ''Trumat Hadeshen'' Removing the ashes of the ''korban olah'' (elevation offering), based on Leviticus 6:1-6.<ref>http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=3&CHAPTER=6</ref>\n* ''korban Tamid'' Perpetual daily offerings: \"...Fire-offering...male yearling [[sheep|lambs]] unblemished two a day...\" based on Numbers 28:1-8.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=4&CHAPTER=28</ref>\n* ''Ketoret'' [[Incense]] [from] [[spice]]s: \"...stacte, onycha, and galbanum, ...and [[frankincense]]...\" Based on Exodus 30:34-36;7-8...<ref name=\"bible.ort.org\"/>\"[[myrrh]], [[Cinnamomum cassia|cassia]], [[spikenard]], [[saffron]], costus, aromatic bark, [[cinnamon]], ley, [[salt]], [[amber]]...\" based on the Babylonian [[Talmud]] ''Kritut'' 6a; Jerusalem Talmud ''Yoma'' 4:5; 33a.\n* ''korban Musaf'' The additional offerings for [[Shabbat]]: \"On the Sabbath...two male lambs...fine [[flour]] for a meal offering mixed with oil and its [[wine]] libation...\" based on Numbers 28:9-10.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* ''korban Rosh Chodesh'' Offering for the new month: ...Two young [[bull]]s, one [[Sheep|ram]], seven lambs...fine flour ...mixed with [[olive oil]]...one he [[goat]]... and its wine libation.\" Based on Numbers 28: 11-15.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* ''Zevachim'' Chapter 5 of [[Mishnah]] ''Zevachim'' is then cited. (It was included in the ''siddur'' at this stage because it discusses all the sacrifices and the sages do not dispute within it):\n**A. ''Eizehu mekoman shel z'vachim'' Places for the ''zevachim korbanot'' to be offered: \"...The slaughter of the bull and the he-goat of Yom Kippur is in the north [of the altar]...\"\n**B. ''Parim hanisrafim'' [[Bull]]s that are completely burned: \"...These are burned in the place where the [altar] ashes are deposited.\"\n**C. ''Chatot hatzibur v'hayachid'' Sin offerings of the community and the individual: \"...The he-goats...are eaten within the [Temple courtyard] curtains by male priests...until midnight.\"\n**D. ''Ha'olah qodesh qodashim'' The elevation offering is among the offerings with a major-degree-of-holiness: \"...it is entirely consumed by fire.\"\n**E. ''Zivchei shalmei tzibur v'ashamot'' Communal peace offerings and guilt offerings: \"...are eaten within the [Temple courtyard] by males of the priesthood...until midnight.\"\n**F. ''Hatodah v'eil nazir qodashim kalim'' The thanksgiving offering and the ram of a Nazirite are offerings of a minor-degree holiness: \"They are eaten throughout the city [of Jerusalem] by anyone, prepared in any manner...until midnight...\"\n**G. ''Sh'lamim qodashim kalim'' The peace offerings are of lesser (lighter) holiness:  \"...Is eaten by the ''kohanim''...throughout the city [of Jerusalem] by anyone...\"\n**H. ''Hab'chor vehama'aser vehapesach qodashim kalim'' The firstborn and tithe of animals and the Passover offering are offerings of lesser (lighter) holiness: \"...The Passover offering is eaten only at night...only if roasted.\"\n* ''Rabbi Yishmael omer'' Rabbi Yishmael says: Through thirteen rules is the Torah elucidated. (Introduction to the ''Sifra'', part of the Oral Law).\n* ''Yehi Ratzon'' (Ending) The study session concludes with a prayer (\"May it be thy will...) for the restoration of the Temple in Jerusalem and the resumption of sacrifices. (...that the Temple be rebuilt speedily in our days, and grant our portion in your Torah and there we shall serve you with reverence as in days of old and in former years. And may the grain offering of Judah and Jerusalem be pleasing to God, as in days of old and in former years.\")\n\nThe [[Amidah]]\n* ''Retzai'' Every the Orthodox [[Amidah]], the central prayer of Jewish services, contains the paragraph: \"Be favorable, Oh Lord our God, to your people Israel and their prayer, and restore the service of the [[Holy of Holies]] of Your House, and accept the fire-offerings of Israel and their prayer with love and favor, and may the service of your people Israel always be favored.\" Conservative Judaism removes the fire-offerings clause from this prayer.\n* ''Yehi Ratzon'' Private recitiation of the Amidah traditionally ends with the ''Yehi Ratzon'' prayer for the restoration of the Temple.\n* The Amidah itself is said to represent liturgically the ''purpose'' of the daily korban, while the recitation of the korbanot sections fulfill the ''formal responsibility'' to perform them, in the absence of the Temple.\n\nThe weekday [[Torah reading]]\n* A set of blessings connected with the weekday Torah reading include a prayer for the [[Third Temple|restoration of the Temple]]: \"May it be the will before our Father who is in heaven to establish the House of our lives and to return his [[Shekhinah]]'' into our midst, speedily, in our days, and let us say Amen.\"\n\n===In Conservative Judaism===\nConservative Judaism disavows the resumption of qorbanot. Consistent with this view, it has deleted prayers for the resumption of sacrifices from the Conservative ''siddur'', including both the morning study section from the sacrifices, prayers for the restoration of qorbanot in the Amidah, and various mentions elsewhere. Consistent with its view that a priesthood and sacrificial system will not be restored, Conservative Judaism has also lifted certain restrictions on ''kohanim'', including limitations on marriage prohibiting marrying a divorced woman or a convert. Conservative Judaism does, however, believe in the restoration of a Temple in some form, and in the continuation of kohanim and [[Levites]] under relaxed requirements, and has retained references to both in its prayer books. Consistent with its stress on the continuity of tradition, many Conservative synagogues have also retained references to [[Shabbat]] and [[Jewish holiday|Festival]] qorbanot, changing all references to sacrifices into the past tense (e.g. the Orthodox \"and there we will sacrifice\" is changed to \"and there they sacrificed\"). Some more liberal Conservative synagogues, however, have removed all references to sacrifices, past or present, from the prayer service. The most recent official Conservative prayer book, [[Sim Shalom]], provides both service alternatives.\n\n===In Reform and Reconstructionist Judaism===\n[[Reform Judaism]] and [[Reconstructionist Judaism]] disavow all belief in a restoration of a Temple, the resumption of qorbanot, or the continuation of identified Cohens or Levites. These branches of Judaism believe that all such practices represent ancient practices inconsistent with the requirements of modernity, and have removed all or virtually all references to qorbanot from their prayer books.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Corban}}\n* [[Abomination (Judaism)]]\n* [[Du\u0161ni Brav]]\n* [[Hakarat HaTov]]\n* [[Holy Qurbana]]\n* [[Incense offering]]\n* [[Kourbania]]\n* [[Priesthood (Ancient Israel)]]\n* [[Psalm 100]]\n* [[Qurbani]]\n* [[Red heifer]]\n* [[Wave offering]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[J. David Bleich|Bleich, J. David]]. \"A Review of Halakhic Literature Pertaining to the Reinstitution of the Sacrificial Order.\" Tradition 9 (1967): 103-24.\n* Myers, Jody Elizabeth. \"Attitudes Towards a Resumption of Sacrificial Worship in the Nineteenth Century.\" Modern Judaism 7, no. 1 (1987): 29-49.\n* Ticker, Jay. The Centrality of Sacrifices as an Answer to Reform in the Thought of Zvi Hirsch Kalischer. Vol. 15, Working Papers in Yiddish and East European Studies, 1975\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=35&letter=S&search=Sacrifices Jewish Encyclopedia.com comprehensive article on the sacrifices]\n* [http://www.tanakhprofiles.org/showappendix.php Sacrifice Handbook: detailed descriptions of the Torah's system of Korbanot] {{in lang|he}}\n* [http://www.webshas.org/zevach/avodos.htm Topical index of Talmud passages on Temple sacrifices]\n{{Jewish prayers}}\n\n[[Category:Tabernacle and Temples in Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Jewish animal sacrifice| ]]\n[[Category:Siddur of Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Shacharit]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Any of a variety of sacrificial offerings described and commanded in the Torah}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Qurbani]], a cognate word that refers to animal sacrifice in Islam}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Karbon (disambiguation)|Karbon]]}}\n{{redirect|Karban|the village in Iran|Karband}}\n{{Judaism}}\n{{Teshuva}}\n\nIn [[Judaism]], the '''korban''' ({{lang|he|\u05e7\u05b8\u05e8\u05b0\u05d1\u05b8\u05bc\u05df}} ''qorb\u0101n''), also spelled '''''qorban''''' or '''''corban''''', is any of a variety of [[Sacrifice|sacrificial offerings]] described and commanded in the [[Torah]]. The plural form is '''korbanot.'''\n\nA korban was a [[kashrut|kosher]] [[animal sacrifice]], such as a [[bull]], [[sheep]], [[goat]],  or a [[dove]] that underwent ''[[shechita]]'' (Jewish ritual slaughter). Sacrifices could also consist of or include [[grain]], [[meal]], [[wine]], or [[incense]].<ref name=\"straightdope.com\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewsforjudaism.org/knowledge/articles/answers/jewish-polemics/texts/scriptural-studies/leviticus-1711/ |title=Leviticus 17:11 |author=Rabbi Michael Skobac |date= |website=Jews for Judaism |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330140559/http://jewsforjudaism.org/knowledge/articles/answers/jewish-polemics/texts/scriptural-studies/leviticus-1711/ |archive-date=30 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://beithamikdash.org.il/%D7%A7%D7%A8%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA/%D7%A2%D7%91%D7%95%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%A7%D7%95%D7%A8%D7%91%D7%9F |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150129185528/http://beithamikdash.org.il/\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea/\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea-\u05d4\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05df |archivedate=2015-01-29 }}</ref> Offerings were often cooked and most of it eaten by the offerer, with parts given to the [[Kohen]] priests and small parts burned on the [[altar (Bible)|altar]] of the [[Temple in Jerusalem]]. Only in special cases was all of the offering given only to God, such as in the case of the [[scapegoat]] and the [[Burnt offering (Judaism)|olah]] offering. <ref name=\"jewfaq.org\" /><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/2203-azazel |chapter=Azazel |author=Morris Jastrow |display-authors=etal |date=1906 |title= Jewish Encyclopedia|publisher= |access-date= 28 December 2018|quote=}}</ref> Common varieties of korban included the ''[[slaughter offering|zevah]]'' ({{lang|he|\u05d6\u05b6\u05d1\u05b7\u05d7}}), [[peace offering]], and ''[[Burnt offering (Judaism)|olah]]''.\n\nThe [[Hebrew Bible]] says that [[God]] commanded the [[Israelites]] to offer offerings and sacrifices on various altars. The sacrifices were only to be offered by the hands of the [[Kohen|Kohanim]]. Before building the [[Temple in Jerusalem]], when the Israelites were in the [[desert]], sacrifices were only to be offered in the [[Tabernacle]]. After the invasion of [[Canaan]], the main sacrificial centre was at [[Shiloh (biblical city)|Shiloh]], though sacrifice also took place at [[Beit Shemesh|Beth-Shemes]]<nowiki/>h,<ref>1 Samuel 6:14\u201315</ref> [[Mizpah in Benjamin|Mizpah]],<ref>1 Samuel 7:9</ref> Ramah,<ref>Samuel 7:17; 9:11\u201324</ref> and Gilgal,<ref>I Samuel 10:8; 11:15;13:9</ref> while family and clan sacrifices were commonplace<ref>1 Samuel\n16:2\u20135</ref> Under Saul the main center of sacrifice was Nob,<ref>1 Samuel 21:1 and the following verses.</ref> though private offerings continued to be made at Shiloh.<ref>2 Samuel 15:12</ref>  David created a new cult center in Jerusalem at the threshing floor of Arauna\u1e25,<ref>Also known as Ornan; 1 Chron. 21:23\u201326</ref> to which he moved the Ark.<ref>2 Samuel 6:17\u201318; 1 Chronicles 16:2, 40</ref><ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica | second edition | vol 17 | sacrifice | pg 645 | Anson Rainey</ref>  According to the Hebrew Bible, after the building of [[Solomon's Temple]], sacrifices were only to be carried out there.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=O'Day|first1=Gail R.|authorlink1=Gail R. O'Day|last2=Petersen|first2=David L.|authorlink2=David L. Petersen|title=Theological Bible Commentary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQWknj4ORJkC&pg=PA151|date=28 April 2009|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=978-1-61164-030-4}}</ref> After the Temple was destroyed, sacrifices were resumed when the [[Second Temple]] was built until it was also destroyed in 70 CE. After the destruction of the Second Temple sacrifices were prohibited because there was no longer a Temple, the only place allowed by [[halakha]] for sacrifices. Offering of sacrifices was briefly reinstated during the [[Jewish\u2013Roman wars]] of the second century CE and was continued in certain communities thereafter.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewfaq.org/qorbanot.htm |title=Qorbanot: Sacrifices and Offerings |last=Rich |first=Tracey R. |date=1998\u20132011 |website=Judaism 101 |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"straightdope.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/2091/why-do-jews-no-longer-sacrifice-animals |title=Why do Jews no longer sacrifice animals? |author=Straight Dope Science Advisory Board |date=17 April 2003 |website=The Straight Dope |publisher= |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://the-tabernacle-place.com/articles/what_is_the_tabernacle |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427011353/http://the-tabernacle-place.com/articles/what_is_the_tabernacle |archive-date=2016-04-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhen [[sacrifice]]s were offered in ancient times, they were offered as a fulfillment of the [[613 commandments]]. Since there is no longer a Temple, modern religious [[Jews]] instead [[prayer|pray]] or give [[tzedakah]] instead.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Diamant|first=Anita|authorlink=Anita Diamant|title=Choosing a Jewish Life: A Handbook for People Converting to Judaism and for Their Family and Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=evEbFIza1c4C&pg=PT156|year=2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8052-1219-8}}</ref>\n\nThe practice and nature of sacrifices in [[Judaism]] are based on the 613 commandments, theology and ''halakha''. According to the Jewish perception the coming of the messiah will not remove the requirement to keep the 613 commandments.<ref name = \"Korn\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Jenson|first1=Robert W.|last2=Korn|first2=Eugene|authorlink2=Eugene Korn|title=Covenant and Hope: Christian and Jewish Reflections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-azoeVhNrcEC&pg=PA119|year=2012|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-6704-9}}</ref> Most [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jews]] believe that animal sacrifice will be resumed once the [[Third Temple]] is built, others believe that prayer and [[tzedakah]] will suffice.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n==Etymology==\n===''Qorban'' and ''qarab''===\nThe [[Semitic root]] {{smallcaps|\u221aqrb}} ({{lang|he|\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1}}) means \"be near\";<ref name=\"BotterweckRinggren2004\">{{cite book|author1=G. Johannes Botterweck|author2=Helmer Ringgren|author3=Heinz-Josef Fabry|title=Theological Dictionary of the Old Testament|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RAwg47G0M2IC&pg=PA136|date=9 January 2004|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-2337-3|page=136}}</ref> other words from the root include ''qarov'' \"close\" and ''qerovim'' \"relatives.\" The same stem is found in Hebrew and, for example, in the [[Akkadian language]] noun ''aqribtu'' \"act of offering.\" The Hebrew feminine noun ''korban'' (plural \u2018\u2019korbanot\u2019\u2019 {{lang|he|\u05e7\u05b8\u05e8\u05b0\u05d1\u05b3\u05bc\u05e0\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea}}) first occurs in the [[Bible]] in [[Book of Leviticus|Leviticus]] {{bibleref2-nb|Leviticus|1:2|HE}} and occurs 80 times in the [[Masoretic Text]]; 40 times in Leviticus, 38 in [[Book of Numbers|Numbers]] and 2 in [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]]. The related form ''qurban'' appears only in the [[Book of Nehemiah]] {{bibleref2-nb|Nehemiah|10:35|HE}} and {{bibleref2-nb|Nehemiah|13:31|HE}} \"wood offering.\" Traditionally the etymology is from the verb stem ''qarab'' and indicates the purpose to bring man close to God.<ref>Solomon Schechter in ''Understanding rabbinic Judaism, from Talmudic to modern times'' ed. Jacob Neusner p229 \"Hence the injunction to bring a Korban (sacrifice) even in this case; the effect of the Korban, as its etymology (Karab) indicates, is to bring man back to God, or rather to facilitate this approach.\"</ref><ref>Judaism in biological perspective: biblical lore and Judaic practices Rick Goldberg - 2008 \"The traditional etymology of korban is of a valuable object \"brought near to God \" (through the sacrificial act).\"</ref>\n\nThe [[Septuagint]] generally translates the term in Greek as ''[[wikt:\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd|\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd]]'' \"gift\", ''[[wikt:\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1|\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1]]'' \"sacrifice\", or ''[[wikt: \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac|\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac]]'' \"offering up\". By the [[Second Temple period]], Hellenistic Jewish texts use korban specifically to mean a vow. The New Testament preserves korban once as a transliterated loan-word for a vow, once also a related noun, ''\u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c2'' \"[[temple treasury]]\", otherwise using ''\u03b4\u1ff6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd'', ''\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03af\u03b1'' or ''\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ac'' and other terms drawn from the [[Septuagint]]. [[Josephus]] also generally uses other words for \"offering\" but uses ''korban'' for the vow of the Nazirites ([[Antiquities of the Jews]] 4:73 / 4,4,4) and cites [[Theophrastus]] as having cited a korban vow among the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrians]] (''[[Against Apion]]'' 1.167 / 1,22,4).<ref>S Zeitlin ''Korban'' The Jewish Quarterly Review, 1962 - JSTOR \"Josephus, in Against Apion, who endeavored to ... Greek world was acquainted with the Judaeans, wrote that, \"The laws of the Tyrians forbid men to swear foreign oaths, among which he [Theophrastus] enumerates some others and particularly that called korban, which oath ...\"</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nContrary to the view that korbanot in the [[Torah]] were for sins, their use was far more complex\u2014only [[sin offering|some korbanot]] were used to atone for unintentional sins, and these sacrifices only accompanied the important required core means of [[Atonement in Judaism|atonement]] to be ever considered legitimate. Besides this one exception, there were the overwhelming majority of other purposes for bringing korbanot, and the expiatory effect is often incidental, and is subject to significant limitations. Korbanot are brought purely for the purpose of communing with God and becoming closer to him. Also, they were brought for the purpose of expressing thanks, gratitude, and love to [[God in Judaism|God]].<ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary.org\">{{cite web |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/qorbanot.html |title=Jewish Practices & Rituals: Sacrifices and Offerings (Karbanot) |last= |first= |date= |website=Jewish Virtual Library |publisher=AICE |access-date=27 August 2017 |quote=}}\n</ref>\n\nFurther, the use of korbanot was circumscribed for certain types of sins. Sins in Judaism consist of different grades of severity:<ref name=\"JE.SIN\"/>\n* The lightest is the ''\u1e25e\u1e6d'', ''\u1e25a\u1e6d\u1e6da'ah'', or ''\u1e25a\u1e6d\u1e6dat''  (lit. \"fault,\" \"shortcoming,\" \"misstep\"), an infraction of a commandment committed in ignorance of the existence or meaning of that command.\n* The second kind is the ''awon'', a breach of a minor commandment committed with a full knowledge of the existence and nature of that commandment (''bemezid''). \n* The gravest kind is the ''pesha'' or ''mered'', a presumptuous and rebellious act against God. Its worst form is the ''resha'', such an act committed with a wicked intention.\nThese three terms are mentioned by the Psalmist (cvi. 6): \"We have sinned [''\u1e25a\u1e6da'nu''], . . . we have committed iniquity [''he-'ewinu''], we have done wickedly [''hirsha'nu]''\" (comp. I Kings viii. 47; Dan. ix. 5).<ref name=\"JE.SIN\">{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13761-sin|title=SIN - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n\nWith few exceptions, korbanot could only be used as a means of atoning for the first type of sin, that is sins committed in ignorance that the thing was a sin.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewfaq.org/qorbanot.htm|title=Judaism 101: Qorbanot: Sacrifices and Offerings|website=www.jewfaq.org}}</ref> In addition, korbanot have no expiating effect unless the person making the offering sincerely repents his or her actions before making the offering, and makes restitution to any person who was harmed by the violation.<ref name=\"jewfaq.org1\"/>\n\n==Hebrew Bible==\n[[File:High Priest Offering Sacrifice of a Goat.jpg|thumb|The High Priest offers the sacrifice of a goat]]\n[[File:High Priest Offering Incense on the Altar.jpg|thumb|The High Priest offers incense on the altar.]]\n\nOfferings are mentioned in the [[Book of Genesis]], but further outlined in the later four books of the Torah, including aspects of their origins and history.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carasik|first=Michael|title=\u05de\u05e7\u05e8\u05d0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea: Leviticus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Alx1rJsiDFAC|year=2009|publisher=Jewish Publication Society|isbn=978-0-8276-0897-9}}, page 3 \"The majority of Leviticus deals with the offerings: how they are to be made, by whom, and where, as well as the ancillary rules that go along ....\"</ref>\n\nOfferings were practiced in the [[Tabernacle]] and during the eras of [[Solomon's Temple]] and the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]] until the total destruction of [[Judea]], Jerusalem, and the Second Temple by the [[Roman Empire]] in 70 CE.<ref>Baruch A. Levine ''In the presence of the Lord: a study of cult and some cultic terms'' 1974   Page 99 \"The Bible gives evidence of two modes of sacrifice in ancient Israel: 1) Altar sacrifices, of which at least some part was consumed by the altar fire, or was burnt as incense, and 2) Offerings placed before the deity and ...\"</ref> Every regular weekday, [[Sabbath]], and many [[Jewish holidays]] had their own unique offerings.<ref>James E Smith ''The Pentateuch'' Page 392 2006 \"Leviticus 23 presents in chronological order a list of \"the Lord's appointed feasts. ... Special offerings were presented each day of the feast.\"</ref>\n\nThe priests performed the offerings first in the ancient [[tabernacle]] and then in the Temple.<ref>Henry W. Soltau ''The Tabernacle, the Priesthood, and the Offerings''- 1972</ref> The Hebrew Bible describes the [[Kohen|kohanim]] (hereditary priesthood) as descendants of [[Aaron]] who meet certain marital and ritual purity requirements.<ref>Martha Himmelfarb ''A kingdom of priests: ancestry and merit in ancient Judaism'' Page 5  2006 \"On the other hand, P and H, the priestly sources, grant the priesthood only to descendants of Aaron, Levi's great-grandson.\"</ref> The [[High Priest of Israel]] played a crucial role in this regard on [[Yom Kippur]], a day when multiple offerings were offered.<ref>Alfred Edersheim ''The Temple -- Its Ministry and Services'' \"The Duties of the High-priest  - Seven days before the Day of Atonement the high-priest left his own house in Jerusalem, and took up his abode in his chambers in the Temple.\"</ref>\n\n===Women and offerings===\nWomen were required to perform a number of offerings, including:{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n* The offerings following childbirth as described in the [[Book of Leviticus]], 12.\n* [[Thank offering]] and its accompanying [[gift offering|meal offering]] following recovery from illness or danger.\n* The [[Passover sacrifice]] on [[Passover]]. Women could offer the sacrifice and hold a [[Passover Seder]] themselves if they wished, even if married.\n* [[Sin offering]]s or [[guilt offering]]s in atonement for transgressions and unintentional errors.\n* Offerings relevant to fulfillment of, or transgression of, the [[Nazirite]] vow.\n* Offerings following cure from certain diseases and unusual bodily discharges.\n\nWomen could also voluntarily participate in a number of other offerings and rituals for which they were not obligated, including:{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n* [[First Fruits]] on the holiday of [[Shavuot]].\n* [[Temple tax]] - The half-[[shekel]] tax for Temple needs.\n* Voluntary offerings, [[peace offering]]s and a variety of other voluntary and donative offerings.\n* ''[[Semicha in sacrifices|Semicha]]'' (laying on hands) of sacrificial animals for sacrifices they were not required to perform (Berachot 19a).\n* Women could slaughter their sacrificial animals themselves if they wished.\n\n===In the Nevi'im===\nMany books of the [[Nevi'im]] section of the [[Hebrew Bible]] such as the [[Book of Isaiah]] and [[Book of Jeremiah]] spoke out against those Israelites who brought forth sacrifices but did not act in accord with the precepts of the Law. The Prophets disparaged sacrifices that were offered without a regeneration of the heart, i.e., a determined turning from sin and returning to God by striving after righteousness ([[Book of Hosea]] 14:1-2, Joel 2:13, Micah 6:6-8). At the same time, prophets stressed the importance of offerings combined with justice and good even as they taught that offerings were unacceptable unless combined with heartfelt repentance and good deeds. [[Malachi]], the last prophet in the Hebrew Bible, emphasized that the goal of repentance is not to end sacrifices, but to make the offerings fit for acceptance once again ([[Book of Malachi]], 3:3-4). Similarly, the [[Book of Isaiah]] despite disparagement of sacrifices without justice, portrays sacrifice as having a role complementary with prayer in a universalistic [[eschatology]] (Isaiah 56:1; 6-7).\n\n==Rabbinical interpretation==\n\n===100 among the 613 commandments===\nAccording to [[Maimonides]], about one hundred of the permanent [[613 commandments]] based on the Torah, by rabbinical enumeration, directly concern sacrifices, excluding those commandments that concern the actual Temple and the priests themselves of which there are about another fifty.<ref>\n# Not to burn anything on the Golden Altar besides incense (Exodus 30:9)\n# To offer only unblemished animals (Leviticus 22:21)\n# Not to dedicate a blemished animal for the altar (Leviticus 22:20)\n# Not to slaughter it (Leviticus 22:22)\n# Not to sprinkle its blood (Leviticus 22:24)\n# Not to burn its ''[[Chelev|khelev]]'' (Leviticus 22:22)\n# Not to offer a temporarily blemished animal (Deuteronomy 17:1)\n# Not to sacrifice blemished animals even if offered by non-Jews (Leviticus 22:25)\n# Not to inflict wounds upon dedicated animals (Leviticus 22:21)\n# To redeem dedicated animals which have become disqualified (Deuteronomy 12:15)\n# To offer only animals which are at least eight days old (Leviticus 22:27)\n# Not to offer animals bought with the wages of a harlot or the animal exchanged for a dog (Deuteronomy 23:19)\n# Not to burn honey or yeast on the altar (Leviticus 2:11)\n# To salt all sacrifices (Leviticus 2:13)\n# Not to omit the salt from sacrifices (Leviticus 2:13)\n# Carry out the procedure of the burnt offering as prescribed in the Torah (Leviticus 1:3)\n# Not to eat its meat (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# Carry out the procedure of the sin offering (Leviticus 6:18)\n# Not to eat the meat of the inner sin offering (Leviticus 6:23)\n# Not to decapitate a fowl brought as a sin offering (Leviticus 5:8)\n# Carry out the procedure of the guilt offering (Leviticus 7:1)\n# The ''kohanim'' must eat the sacrificial meat in the Temple (Exodus 29:33)\n# The ''kohanim'' must not eat the meat outside the Temple courtyard (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# A non-''kohen'' must not eat sacrificial meat (Exodus 29:33)\n# To follow the procedure of the peace offering (Leviticus 7:11)\n# Not to eat the meat of minor sacrifices before sprinkling the blood (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# To bring meal offerings as prescribed in the Torah (Leviticus 2:1)\n# Not to put oil on the meal offerings of wrongdoers (Leviticus 5:11)\n# Not to put frankincense on the meal offerings of wrongdoers (Leviticus 3:11)\n# Not to eat the meal offering of the High Priest (Leviticus 6:16)\n# Not to bake a meal offering as leavened bread (Leviticus 6:10)\n# The ''kohanim'' must eat the remains of the meal offerings (Leviticus 6:9)\n# To bring all avowed and freewill offerings to the Temple on the first subsequent festival (Deuteronomy 12:5-6)\n# To offer all sacrifices in the Temple (Deuteronomy 12:11)\n# To bring all sacrifices from outside Israel to the Temple (Deuteronomy 12:26)\n# Not to slaughter sacrifices outside the courtyard (of the Temple) (Leviticus 17:4)\n# Not to offer any sacrifices outside the courtyard (of the Temple) (Deuteronomy 12:13)\n# To offer two lambs every day (Numbers 28:3)\n# To light a fire on the altar every day (Leviticus 6:6)\n# Not to extinguish this fire (Leviticus 6:6)\n# To remove the ashes from the altar every day (Leviticus 6:3)\n# To burn incense every day (Exodus 30:7)\n# The ''Kohen Gadol'' must bring a meal offering every day (Leviticus 6:13)\n# To bring two additional lambs as burnt offerings on Shabbat (Numbers 28:9)\n# To bring additional offerings on the New Month (''[[Rosh Khodesh]]'') (Numbers 28:11)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Passover]] (Numbers 28:19)\n# To offer the wave offering from the meal of the new wheat (Leviticus 23:10)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Shavuot]] (Numbers 28:26)\n# To bring two leaves to accompany the above sacrifice (Leviticus 23:17)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Rosh Hashana]] (Numbers 29:2)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Yom Kippur]] (Numbers 29:8)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Sukkot]] (Numbers 29:13)\n# To bring additional offerings on [[Shmini Atzeret]] (Numbers 29:35)\n# Not to eat sacrifices which have become unfit or blemished (Deuteronomy 14:3)\n# Not to eat from sacrifices offered with improper intentions (Leviticus 7:18)\n# Not to leave sacrifices past the time allowed for eating them (Leviticus 22:30)\n# Not to eat from that which was left over (Leviticus 19:8)\n# Not to eat from sacrifices which became impure (Leviticus 7:19)\n# An impure person must not eat from sacrifices (Leviticus 7:20)\n# To burn the leftover sacrifices (Leviticus 7:17)\n# To burn all impure sacrifices (Leviticus 7:19)\n# To follow the [sacrificial] procedure of Yom Kippur in the sequence prescribed in ''Parshah [[Acharei]] Mot'' (After the death of [[Aaron]]'s sons...) (Leviticus 16:3)\n# One who profaned property must repay what he profaned plus a fifth and bring a sacrifice (Leviticus 5:16)\n# Not to work consecrated animals (Deuteronomy 15:19)\n# Not to shear the fleece of consecrated animals (Deuteronomy 15:19)\n# To slaughter the paschal sacrifice at the specified time (Exodus 12:6)\n# Not to slaughter it while in possession of leaven (Exodus 23:18)\n# Not to leave the fat overnight (Exodus 23:18)\n# To slaughter the second Paschal lamb (Numbers 9:11)\n# To eat the [[Passover sacrifice]] with ''[[matzah]]'' and ''marror'' on the night of the 15th of Nissan (Exodus 12:8)\n# To eat the second Paschal Lamb on the night of the 15th of Iyar (Numbers 9:11)\n# Not to eat the Paschal meat raw or boiled (Exodus 12:9)\n# Not to take the Paschal meat from the confines of the group (Exodus 12:46)\n# An apostate must not eat from it (Exodus 12:43)\n# A permanent or temporary hired worker must not eat from it (Exodus 12:45)\n# An uncircumcised male must not eat from it (Exodus 12:48)\n# Not to break any bones from the paschal offering (Exodus 12:46)\n# Not to break any bones from the second paschal offering (Numbers 9:12)\n# Not to leave any meat from the Paschal offering over until morning (Exodus 12:10)\n# Not to leave the second Paschal meat over until morning (Numbers 9:12)\n# Not to leave the meat of the holiday offering of the 14th until the 16th (Deuteronomy 16:4)\n# To celebrate on  [[Passover]], [[Shavuot]], and [[Sukkot]] at the [[Temple of Solomon|Temple]] (bring a peace offering) (Exodus 23:14)\n# To rejoice on these three Festivals (bring a peace offering) (Deuteronomy 16:14)\n# Not to appear at the Temple without offerings (Deuteronomy 16:16)\n# Not to refrain from rejoicing with, and giving gifts to, the Levites (Deuteronomy 12:19)\n# The ''kohanim'' must not eat unblemished firstborn animals outside Jerusalem (Deuteronomy 12:17)\n# Every person must bring a sin offering for his transgression (Leviticus 4:27)\n# Bring an ''asham talui'' when uncertain of guilt (Leviticus 5:17-18)\n# Bring an ''asham vadai'' when guilt is ascertained (Leviticus 5:25)\n# Bring an ''oleh v'yored'' offering (if the person is wealthy, an animal; if poor, a bird or meal offering) (Leviticus 5:7-11)\n# The [[Sanhedrin]] must bring an offering when it rules in error (Leviticus 4:13)\n# A woman who had a running issue (unnatural [[Menstrual cycle|menstrual]] flow) must bring an offering after she goes to the [[Mikveh|ritual bath]] (Leviticus 15:28-29)\n# A woman who gave birth must bring an offering after she goes to the bath (Leviticus 12:6)\n# A man who had a running issue (unnatural [[semen]] flow) must bring an offering after he goes to the bath (Leviticus 15:13-14)\n# A ''metzora'' (a person with ''[[tzaraas]]'')  must bring an offering after going to the [[Mikveh]] (Leviticus 14:10)\n# Not to substitute another beast for one set apart for sacrifice ([[temurah (Halacha)|temurah]]) (Leviticus 27:10)\n# The new animal, in addition to the substituted one, retains consecration (Leviticus 27:10)\n# Not to change consecrated animals from one type of offering to another (Leviticus 27:26)\n# Carry out the procedure of the [[red heifer]] (Numbers 19:2)\n# Carry out the laws of the sprinkling water (Numbers 19:21)\n# Break the neck of a calf by the river valley following an unsolved murder (Deuteronomy 21:4)</ref>\n\n===Instructions in Mishnah and Talmud===\nThe [[Mishnah]] and [[Talmud]] devote a very large section, known as a ''seder'', to the study and analysis of this subject known as ''[[Kodashim|Qodashim]]'', whereby all the detailed varieties of korbanot are enumerated and analyzed in great logical depth, such as ''qodshim kalim'' (\"of minor degree of sanctity\") and ''qodashei qodashim'' (\"of major degree of sanctity\"). In addition, large parts of every other book of the Talmud discuss various kinds of sacrifices. ''Pesachim'' is largely devoted to a discussion of how to offer the [[Passover sacrifice]]. ''Yoma'' contains a detailed discussion of the offerings and Temple ritual on Yom Kippur (Day of Atonement), and there are sections in ''seder Moed'' (Festivals) for the special offerings and Temple ritual for other major Jewish holidays. ''Sheqalim'' discusses the annual half-shekel offering for Temple maintenance and Temple governance and management, ''Nashim'' discusses the offerings made by [[Nazirite]]s and the suspected adultress, etc.\n\nThe Talmud provides extensive details not only on how to perform sacrifices but how to adjudicate difficult cases, such what to do if a mistake was made and whether improperly performing one of the required ritual elements invalidates it or not. The Talmud explains how to roast the Passover offering, how to dash blood from different kinds of sacrifices upon the altar, how to prepare the incense, the regulatory code for the system of taxation that financed the priesthood and public sacrifices, and numerous other details.\n\n===Rationale and rabbinic commentary===\n[[Maimonides]], a medieval Jewish scholar, drew on the early critiques of the need for sacrifice, taking the view that God always held sacrifice inferior to prayer and philosophical meditation. However, God understood that the Israelites were used to the animal sacrifices that the surrounding pagan tribes used as the primary way to commune with their gods. As such, in Maimonides' view, it was only natural that Israelites would believe that sacrifice would be a necessary part of the relationship between God and man. Maimonides concludes that God's decision to allow sacrifices was a concession to human psychological limitations. It would have been too much to have expected the Israelites to leap from pagan worship to prayer and meditation in one step. In ''[[The Guide for the Perplexed]]'', he writes:\n{{quote|But the custom which was in those days general among men, and the general mode of worship in which the Israelites were brought up consisted in sacrificing animals... It was in accordance with the wisdom and plan of God...that God did not command us to give up and to discontinue all these manners of service. For to obey such a commandment would have been contrary to the nature of man, who generally cleaves to that to which he is used; it would in those days have made the same impression as a prophet would make at present [the 12th Century] if he called us to the service of God and told us in His name, that we should not pray to God nor fast, nor seek His help in time of trouble; that we should serve Him in thought, and not by any action.<ref>Book III, Chapter 32. Translated by M. Friedlander, 1904, ''The Guide for the Perplexed'', Dover Publications, 1956 edition</ref>}}\n\nIn contrast, many others such as [[Nahmanides]] (in his commentary on Leviticus 1:9) disagreed. Nahmanides cites the fact that the Torah records the practices of animal and other sacrifices from the times of [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]] and earlier. Indeed, the purpose of recounting the [[Binding of Isaac|near sacrifice of Isaac]] was to illustrate the sublime significance and need of animal sacrifices as supplanting the abomination of human sacrifices.\n\n===In spiritual practice===\nThe korban also has a spiritual meaning, and refers to some part of an individual's ego, which is given up as a sacrifice to God in honor of the mortality of the worshipper. In keeping with the root of the word, meaning to draw close, and to the common usage as the sacrifice of an animal, so too can the worshipper sacrifice something of this world in order to become closer to God.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =  Dubov\n  | first =  Nissan Dovid \n  | title = Jewish Meditation\n  | publisher =Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center\n  | url = http://www.chabad.org/library/article.asp?AID=361886\n  | accessdate =  2006-08-17}}</ref>\n\n==The end of sacrifices==\nWith the destruction of the Second Temple in Jerusalem by the Romans, the Jewish practice of offering korbanot stopped for all intents and purposes. Despite subsequent intermittent periods of small Jewish groups offering the traditional sacrifices on the Temple Mount, the practice effectively ended.\n\n[[Rabbinic Judaism]] was forced to undergo a significant development in response to this change; no longer could Judaism revolve around the Temple services. The destruction of the Temple led to a development of Judaism in the direction of text study, prayer, and personal observance. [[Orthodox Judaism]] regards this as being largely an alternative way of fulfilling the obligations of the Temple. Other branches of Judaism ([[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]], [[Reform Judaism|Reform]], and [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]]) regard the korbanot as an ancient ritual that will not return. A range of responses is recorded in classical rabbinic literature, describing this subject.\n\n:Once, Rabbi Yohanan ben Zakkai was walking with his disciple, Rabbi Y'hoshua, near Jerusalem after the destruction of the Temple. Rabbi Y'hoshua looked at the Temple ruins and said \"Alas for us!! The place that atoned for the sins of the people Israel lies in ruins!\" Then Rabbi Yohannan ben Zakkai spoke to him these words of comfort:  'Be not grieved, my son. There is another equally meritorious way of gaining ritual atonement, even though the Temple is destroyed. We can still gain ritual atonement through deeds of loving-kindness. For it is written \"Loving kindness I desire, not sacrifice.\" (Hosea 6:6)\n:[[Midrash]] Avot D'Rabbi Nathan 4:5\n\nIn the [[Babylonian Talmud]], a number of sages opined that following Jewish law, doing charitable deeds, and studying Jewish texts is greater than performing animal sacrifices.\n\n:Rabbi Elazar said: Doing righteous deeds of charity is greater than offering all of the sacrifices, as it is written: \"Doing charity and justice is more desirable to the Lord than sacrifice\" (Proverbs 21:3).\n:Babylonian Talmud, Sukkah 49\n\nNonetheless, numerous texts of the Talmud stress the importance of and hope for eventual re-introduction of sacrifices, and regard their loss as a terrible tragedy. Partaking of sacrificial offerings was compared to eating directly at one's Father's table, whose loss synagogue worship does not quite entirely replace. One example is in ''Berachot'':\n:And I said to him: I heard a heavenly voice that was cooing like a dove and saying, \"Woe to the children because of whose sins I destroyed My house, and burned My temple, and exiled them among the nations of the world. And he [Elijah the prophet] said to me: \"By your life and the life of your head! It is not only at this moment that [the heavenly voice] says this. But on each and every day it says this three times. And not only this, but at the time that the people of Israel enter the synagogues and houses of study, and respond (in the [[Kaddish]]) \"May His great name be blessed\", the Holy One, Blessed is He, shakes His head and says: \"Fortunate for the king who is praised this way in his house. What is there for the Father who has exiled His children. And woe to the children who have been exiled from their Father's table.\"  (Talmud ''Berachot'' 3a).\n\nAnother example is in ''Sheqalim'':\n:Rabbi Akiva said: Shimon Ben Loga related the following to me: I was once collecting grasses, and I saw a child from the [[House of Avitnas]] (the incense-makers). And I saw that he cried, and I saw that he laughed. I said to him, \"My son, why did you cry?\" He said, Because of the glory of my Father's house that has decreased.\" I asked \"And why did you laugh?\" He said to me \"Because of the glory prepared for the righteous in the future.\" I asked \"And what did you see?\" [that brought on these emotions]. \"The herb ''[[Maaleh Ashan|maaleh ashan]]'' is growing next to me. [''Maaleh Ashan'' is the secret ingredient in the incense that made the smoke rise, which according to the Talmud the [[House of Avitnas]] never revealed.]\"\n\n===Liturgical attention to end of sacrifices===\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2016}}\nNumerous details of the daily religious practice of an ordinary Jew are connected to keeping memory of the rhythm of the life of the Temple and its sacrifices. For example, the Mishna begins with a statement that the [[Shema Yisrael]] prayer is to be recited in the evening at the time when Kohanim who were ''[[Tumah and taharah|tamei]]'' (ritually impure) are permitted to enter to eat their [[heave offering]] (a food-tithe given to priests) following purification. A detailed discussion of the obligations of tithing, ritual purity, and other elements central to the Temple and priesthood is required in order to determine the meaning of this contemporary daily Jewish obligation.\n\n===Other occasions===\nJewish services for [[Shabbat]], Jewish holidays and other occasions include special prayers for the restoration of sacrifices. For example, the traditional Yom Kippur liturgy contains repeated prayers for the restoration of sacrifices and every [[High Holiday]] [[Amidah]] contains [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 56:7:\n:Even them will I bring to My holy mountain, and make them joyful in My house of prayer; their burnt-offerings and their sacrifices shall be acceptable upon Mine altar; for My house shall be called a house of prayer for all peoples.<ref name=\"mechon-mamre.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mechon-mamre.org/p/pt/pt1056.htm|title=Isaiah 56 / Hebrew - English Bible / Mechon-Mamre|website=www.mechon-mamre.org}}</ref>\n\n==Modern view and resumption of sacrifices==\n\n===Future of sacrifices in Judaism===\n{{see also| Temple in Jerusalem}}\nThe prevailing belief among rabbinic Jews is that in the [[Messianic Age|messianic era]], the [[Messiah in Judaism|Messiah]] will come and a [[Third Temple]] will be built. It is believed that the korbanot will be reinstituted, but to what extent and for how long is unknown. Some biblical and classical rabbinic sources hold that most or all sacrifices will not need to be offered.\n\n* In the future all sacrifices, with the exception of the Thanksgiving-sacrifice, will be discontinued. (Midrash Vayikra Rabbah 9:7)\n* All sacrifices will be annulled in the future. (Tanchuma Emor 14, Vayikra Rabbah 9:7)\n* Then the grain-offering of Judah and Jerusalem will be pleasing to God as in the days of old, and as in ancient years. (Malachi 3:4)\n* It is impossible to go suddenly from one extreme to the other;...the custom which was in those days general among all men, and the general mode of worship in which the Israelites were brought up consisted of sacrificing animals in the temples... For this reason God allowed this kind of service to continue.  The sacrificial system is not the primary object, rather supplications, and prayer. (Maimonides, The Guide to the Perplexed III 32)\n\nThe majority view of classical rabbis is that the Torah's commandments will still be applicable and in force during the messianic era. However, a significant minority of rabbis held that most of the commandments will be nullified in the messianic era, thus holding that sacrifices will not be reinstated. Examples of such rabbinic views include:\n* Babylonian Talmud, Tractate Niddah 61b and Tractate Shabbat 151b.\n* Midrash Shochar Tov (Mizmor 146:5) states that God will permit what is now forbidden.\n\n[[Orthodox Judaism]] holds that in the messianic era, most or all of the korbanot will be reinstituted, at least for a time. [[Conservative Judaism]] and [[Reform Judaism]], hold that no animal sacrifices will be offered in a rebuilt Temple at all, following the position of Tanchuma Emor 14 and Vayikra Rabbah 9:7.\n\n===Nineteenth and twentieth century===\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2017}}\nIn the 1800s a number of Orthodox rabbis studied the idea of reinstating korbanot on the Temple Mount, even though the messianic era had not yet arrived and the Temple was not rebuilt. A number of [[responsa]] concluded that within certain parameters, it is permissible according to Jewish law to offer such sacrifices.\n\nDuring the early 20th century, [[Israel Meir Kagan]] advised some followers to set up special ''[[yeshiva]]s'' for married students known as ''Qodshim [[Kolel]]im'' that would specialize in the study of the korbanot and study with greater intensity the ''qodshim'' sections of the [[Talmud]] in order to prepare for the arrival of the Jewish Messiah who would oversee the rebuilding of the original Temple of Solomon in [[Jerusalem]] that would be known as the [[Third Temple]]. His advice was taken seriously and today there are a number of well-established [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] institutions in [[Israel]] that focus solely on the subject of the korbanot, ''qodshim'', and the needs of the future Jewish Temple, such as the [[Brisk tradition and Soloveitchik dynasty]].\n\n===Efforts to restore korbanot===\n{{Main|The Third Temple}}\nA few groups, notably the [[Temple Institute]] and the [[Temple Mount Faithful]], have petitioned the Israeli government to rebuild a Third Temple on the [[Temple Mount]] and restore sacrificial worship. The Israeli government has not responded favorably. Most Orthodox Jews regard rebuilding a Temple as an activity for a Jewish Messiah as part of a future [[Jewish eschatology]], and most non-Orthodox Jews do not believe in the restoration of sacrificial worship at all. The Temple Institute has been constructing ritual objects in preparation for a resumption of sacrifices.\n\n==View among modern Jewish denominations==\n\n===Contemporary Orthodox Judaism===\nToday Orthodox Judaism includes mention of each korban on either a daily basis in the ''[[siddur]]'' (daily prayer book), or in the ''[[machzor]]'' (holiday prayerbook) as part of the prayers for the relevant days concerned. They are also referred to in the prayerbooks of Conservative Judaism, in an abbreviated fashion.\n\nOn each Jewish holiday the sections in the Torah mentioning that festival's korbanot is read out loud in [[synagogue]].\n\n====Daily services====\nIn the very early morning daily ''[[Shacharit]]'' prayers for example, they include the following in order of mention, actually called the korbanot. The following example is taken from the [[Nusach Ashkenaz]].\n* ''Kiyor'' Describing the basin containing pure water to wash up before touching the korbanot (offerings), based on Exodus 30: 17-21.<ref name=\"bible.ort.org\">http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=2&CHAPTER=30</ref>\n* ''Trumat Hadeshen'' Removing the ashes of the ''korban olah'' (elevation offering), based on Leviticus 6:1-6.<ref>http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=3&CHAPTER=6</ref>\n* ''korban Tamid'' Perpetual daily offerings: \"...Fire-offering...male yearling [[sheep|lambs]] unblemished two a day...\" based on Numbers 28:1-8.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://bible.ort.org/books/pentd2.asp?ACTION=displaypage&BOOK=4&CHAPTER=28</ref>\n* ''Ketoret'' [[Incense]] [from] [[spice]]s: \"...stacte, onycha, and galbanum, ...and [[frankincense]]...\" Based on Exodus 30:34-36;7-8...<ref name=\"bible.ort.org\"/>\"[[myrrh]], [[Cinnamomum cassia|cassia]], [[spikenard]], [[saffron]], costus, aromatic bark, [[cinnamon]], ley, [[salt]], [[amber]]...\" based on the Babylonian [[Talmud]] ''Kritut'' 6a; Jerusalem Talmud ''Yoma'' 4:5; 33a.\n* ''korban Musaf'' The additional offerings for [[Shabbat]]: \"On the Sabbath...two male lambs...fine [[flour]] for a meal offering mixed with oil and its [[wine]] libation...\" based on Numbers 28:9-10.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* ''korban Rosh Chodesh'' Offering for the new month: ...Two young [[bull]]s, one [[Sheep|ram]], seven lambs...fine flour ...mixed with [[olive oil]]...one he [[goat]]... and its wine libation.\" Based on Numbers 28: 11-15.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* ''Zevachim'' Chapter 5 of [[Mishnah]] ''Zevachim'' is then cited. (It was included in the ''siddur'' at this stage because it discusses all the sacrifices and the sages do not dispute within it):\n**A. ''Eizehu mekoman shel z'vachim'' Places for the ''zevachim korbanot'' to be offered: \"...The slaughter of the bull and the he-goat of Yom Kippur is in the north [of the altar]...\"\n**B. ''Parim hanisrafim'' [[Bull]]s that are completely burned: \"...These are burned in the place where the [altar] ashes are deposited.\"\n**C. ''Chatot hatzibur v'hayachid'' Sin offerings of the community and the individual: \"...The he-goats...are eaten within the [Temple courtyard] curtains by male priests...until midnight.\"\n**D. ''Ha'olah qodesh qodashim'' The elevation offering is among the offerings with a major-degree-of-holiness: \"...it is entirely consumed by fire.\"\n**E. ''Zivchei shalmei tzibur v'ashamot'' Communal peace offerings and guilt offerings: \"...are eaten within the [Temple courtyard] by males of the priesthood...until midnight.\"\n**F. ''Hatodah v'eil nazir qodashim kalim'' The thanksgiving offering and the ram of a Nazirite are offerings of a minor-degree holiness: \"They are eaten throughout the city [of Jerusalem] by anyone, prepared in any manner...until midnight...\"\n**G. ''Sh'lamim qodashim kalim'' The peace offerings are of lesser (lighter) holiness:  \"...Is eaten by the ''kohanim''...throughout the city [of Jerusalem] by anyone...\"\n**H. ''Hab'chor vehama'aser vehapesach qodashim kalim'' The firstborn and tithe of animals and the Passover offering are offerings of lesser (lighter) holiness: \"...The Passover offering is eaten only at night...only if roasted.\"\n* ''Rabbi Yishmael omer'' Rabbi Yishmael says: Through thirteen rules is the Torah elucidated. (Introduction to the ''Sifra'', part of the Oral Law).\n* ''Yehi Ratzon'' (Ending) The study session concludes with a prayer (\"May it be thy will...) for the restoration of the Temple in Jerusalem and the resumption of sacrifices. (...that the Temple be rebuilt speedily in our days, and grant our portion in your Torah and there we shall serve you with reverence as in days of old and in former years. And may the grain offering of Judah and Jerusalem be pleasing to God, as in days of old and in former years.\")\n\nThe [[Amidah]]\n* ''Retzai'' Every the Orthodox [[Amidah]], the central prayer of Jewish services, contains the paragraph: \"Be favorable, Oh Lord our God, to your people Israel and their prayer, and restore the service of the [[Holy of Holies]] of Your House, and accept the fire-offerings of Israel and their prayer with love and favor, and may the service of your people Israel always be favored.\" Conservative Judaism removes the fire-offerings clause from this prayer.\n* ''Yehi Ratzon'' Private recitiation of the Amidah traditionally ends with the ''Yehi Ratzon'' prayer for the restoration of the Temple.\n* The Amidah itself is said to represent liturgically the ''purpose'' of the daily korban, while the recitation of the korbanot sections fulfill the ''formal responsibility'' to perform them, in the absence of the Temple.\n\nThe weekday [[Torah reading]]\n* A set of blessings connected with the weekday Torah reading include a prayer for the [[Third Temple|restoration of the Temple]]: \"May it be the will before our Father who is in heaven to establish the House of our lives and to return his [[Shekhinah]]'' into our midst, speedily, in our days, and let us say Amen.\"\n\n===In Conservative Judaism===\nConservative Judaism disavows the resumption of qorbanot. Consistent with this view, it has deleted prayers for the resumption of sacrifices from the Conservative ''siddur'', including both the morning study section from the sacrifices, prayers for the restoration of qorbanot in the Amidah, and various mentions elsewhere. Consistent with its view that a priesthood and sacrificial system will not be restored, Conservative Judaism has also lifted certain restrictions on ''kohanim'', including limitations on marriage prohibiting marrying a divorced woman or a convert. Conservative Judaism does, however, believe in the restoration of a Temple in some form, and in the continuation of kohanim and [[Levites]] under relaxed requirements, and has retained references to both in its prayer books. Consistent with its stress on the continuity of tradition, many Conservative synagogues have also retained references to [[Shabbat]] and [[Jewish holiday|Festival]] qorbanot, changing all references to sacrifices into the past tense (e.g. the Orthodox \"and there we will sacrifice\" is changed to \"and there they sacrificed\"). Some more liberal Conservative synagogues, however, have removed all references to sacrifices, past or present, from the prayer service. The most recent official Conservative prayer book, [[Sim Shalom]], provides both service alternatives.\n\n===In Reform and Reconstructionist Judaism===\n[[Reform Judaism]] and [[Reconstructionist Judaism]] disavow all belief in a restoration of a Temple, the resumption of qorbanot, or the continuation of identified Cohens or Levites. These branches of Judaism believe that all such practices represent ancient practices inconsistent with the requirements of modernity, and have removed all or virtually all references to qorbanot from their prayer books.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Corban}}\n* [[Abomination (Judaism)]]\n* [[Du\u0161ni Brav]]\n* [[Hakarat HaTov]]\n* [[Holy Qurbana]]\n* [[Incense offering]]\n* [[Kourbania]]\n* [[Priesthood (Ancient Israel)]]\n* [[Psalm 100]]\n* [[Qurbani]]\n* [[Red heifer]]\n* [[Wave offering]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[J. David Bleich|Bleich, J. David]]. \"A Review of Halakhic Literature Pertaining to the Reinstitution of the Sacrificial Order.\" Tradition 9 (1967): 103-24.\n* Myers, Jody Elizabeth. \"Attitudes Towards a Resumption of Sacrificial Worship in the Nineteenth Century.\" Modern Judaism 7, no. 1 (1987): 29-49.\n* Ticker, Jay. The Centrality of Sacrifices as an Answer to Reform in the Thought of Zvi Hirsch Kalischer. Vol. 15, Working Papers in Yiddish and East European Studies, 1975\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=35&letter=S&search=Sacrifices Jewish Encyclopedia.com comprehensive article on the sacrifices]\n* [http://www.tanakhprofiles.org/showappendix.php Sacrifice Handbook: detailed descriptions of the Torah's system of Korbanot] {{in lang|he}}\n* [http://www.webshas.org/zevach/avodos.htm Topical index of Talmud passages on Temple sacrifices]\n{{Jewish prayers}}\n\n[[Category:Tabernacle and Temples in Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Jewish animal sacrifice| ]]\n[[Category:Siddur of Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Shacharit]]\n", "name_user": "SamsonKriger", "label": "safe", "comment": "Exchanged language of \"cult\" for center. Also added explanation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korban"}
{"title_page": "Norfolk and Western 1218", "text_new": "{{short description|Preserved N&W class A locomotive}}\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name = Norfolk & Western No. 1218\n| powertype = Steam\n| image   = N&W 1218 Brocton, OH on August 6, 1988 (22541514277).jpg\n| caption = 1218 leads an excursion train at Brocton, Ohio, on August 6, 1988\n| builder = [[Norfolk & Western Railway|N&W's]] [[Roanoke Shops]]\n| serialnumber     = 340\n| builddate        = June 1943\n| whytetype        = [[2-6-6-4]]\n| uicclass         = (1\u2032C)C2\u2032 h4\n| gauge            = {{track gauge|ussg}}\n| leadingdiameter  = {{convert|33|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| driverdiameter   = {{convert|70|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| trailingdiameter = {{convert|42|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length           = {{convert|121|ft|9+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}} including tender<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| width            = {{convert|11|ft|2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| height           = {{convert|16|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| axleload         = {{convert|72000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| weightondrivers  = {{convert|433350|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| locoweight       = {{convert|573000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| locotenderweight = {{convert|951600|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| fueltype         = [[Coal]]\n| fuelcap          = {{convert|60000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| watercap         = {{convert|22000|USgal|abbr=on}}\n| boilerpressure   = {{convert|300|lbf/in2|MPa|2|abbr=on}}\n| firearea         = {{convert|122|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| fireboxarea      = {{convert|587|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| tubesandflues    = {{convert|6052|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| superheaterarea  = {{convert|2703|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| cylindercount    = Four, simple articulated\n| cylindersize     = {{convert|24|x|30|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| valvegear        = [[Baker valve gear|Baker]]\n| valvetype        = Piston valves\n| maxspeed         = 70+ mph<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| poweroutput      = {{convert|5400|hp|abbr=on}}\n| tractiveeffort   = Starting: {{convert|125897|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on}} Continuous: {{convert|114000|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader>{{cite news| title=All Aboard - Steam locomotive to power day-long excursions from Greenville| newspaper=Gaffney Leader| location=Gaffney, SC| date=March 20, 1987| page=7| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549054/the_gaffney_ledger/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n| factorofadhesion = 3.44\n| operator         = [[Norfolk & Western Railway]]\u2192[[Norfolk Southern]]\n| operatorclass    = [[Norfolk and Western Railway class A|A]]\n| numinclass       = 19 of 43\n| locale           = [[United States]], [[Southern United States|South]] and [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]]\n| retiredate       = 1959 <small>(revenue)</small><ref name=GaffneyLeader /><br>1991 <small>(excursion)</small>\n| restoredate      = April 1987<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| currentowner     = [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]]\n| disposition      = On static display, based in [[Roanoke, Virginia]]\n}}\n'''Norfolk and Western No. 1218''' is a four-cylinder simple articulated [[steam locomotive]] with a [[2-6-6-4]] ([[Whyte notation|Whyte system]]) wheel arrangement. The [[Norfolk & Western Railway]] built it in 1943 at its [[Roanoke Shops]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]], and was part of the Norfolk & Western's class A fleet of fast freight locomotives.<ref>{{cite news| title=Travel Talk| newspaper=Muncie Evening Press| location=Muncie, IN| date=August 13, 1987| page=26| first=Ellen| last=Ball| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23548921/muncie_evening_press/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> It was retired from regular revenue service in 1959, it was later restored by [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] and operated it in [[Excursion train|excursion service]] from 1987 to 1991. Today it is on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n\n==Historic significance== \nNo. 1218 is the sole survivor of the [[Norfolk and Western Railway|Norfolk and Western]]'s class A locomotives, and the only surviving 2-6-6-4 steam locomotive in the world.  While smaller than Union Pacific's famous and more numerous \"[[4-6-6-4|Challenger]]\" Class of 4-6-6-4 locomotives, Norfolk and Western's design racked up unmatched records of performance in service.\n\nDuring 1218's excursion career, it was the most powerful operational steam locomotive in the world,<ref>{{cite news| title=Mighty locomotive will steam to Fort Wayne| newspaper=Battle Creek Enquirer| location=Battle Creek, MI| date=June 24, 1990| page=20| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23548823/battle_creek_enquirer/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> with a [[tractive effort]] of {{convert|125,897|lbf|kN|2|lk=on}}, well above [[Union Pacific 3985]], the next-strongest-pulling operational steam locomotive, with a tractive effort of {{convert|97350|lbf|kN|1|abbr=on|disp=sqbr}}). Since May 2019, however, No. 1218 became the locomotive with the second highest tractive effort, after [[Union Pacific 4014]], which has a tractive effort of {{convert|135375|lbf|kN|abbr=on}}. Unlike diesel-electric locomotives of similar high tractive effort (for starting heavy trains) but typical for a steam locomotive, it could easily run at 70 miles per hour (113&nbsp;km/h) and more.\n\n==Operational history==\nNorfolk and Western used No. 1218 and the other class A locomotives primarily for fast freight trains, but they also pulled heavy coal trains on the flatter districts of the Norfolk & Western system, and reportedly even pulled heavy passenger trains at times.\n\nIn 1959, when the 1218 was retired, it was purchased by the [[Union Carbide|Union Carbide Co.]] in [[Charleston, West Virginia]], where it was used as a stationary boiler at a chemical plant.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=73-74}}.</ref> In 1965, No. 1218 was repurchased by [[New England]] millionaire [[F. Nelson Blount]] for his locomotive collection at [[Steamtown, U.S.A.]] in [[Bellows Falls, Vermont]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> Three years later, its former owner Norfolk & Western did a cosmetic restoration on 1218 at their East End Shops in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] (the same place where it was built).<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> After that, it was put on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation|Roanoke Transportation Museum]] in 1971.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/>\n\n[[File:N&W 1218, north of Marion, Ohio on August 16, 1987 (22166418064).jpg|thumb|left|Norfolk and Western Railway 1218 in excursion service in 1987]]\n\nIn 1982, the Norfolk & Western and the Southern Railway were both merged to form the new [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] (NS).<ref name=\"Wrinn2000p61\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|p=61}}.</ref> On May 10, 1985, No. 1218 was moved out of the park by a pair of NS diesels to be overhauled at the Irondale Steam Shop in [[Irondale, Alabama]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> In 1987, No. 1218 was moved under its power for the first time in 28 years and operated for main-line excursion service on Norfolk Southern's steam program.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp79-82\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=79-82}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, No. 1218 traveled to [[St. Louis|Saint Louis, Missouri]], where it met up with locomotives [[St. Louis Southwestern 819|St Louis Southwestern 4-8-4 No. 819]], [[St. Louis\u2013San Francisco 1522|St Louis San Francisco 4-8-2 No. 1522]], and [[Union Pacific 844|Union Pacific 4-8-4 No. 844]] to participate in the [[National Railway Historical Society|NRHS]] convention at the former [[Union Station (St. Louis)|Union Station]].\n\nOn November 3, 1991, during Norfolk Southern's 25th Anniversary of their Steam Program, No. 1218 joined [[Southern Railway 4501|Southern Railway MS Class 2-8-2 No. 4501]] and [[Norfolk and Western 611|Norfolk and Western J Class No. 611]] to triple head a 28-car passenger excursion train from Chattanooga to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=90\u201391}}.</ref> At [[Ooltewah, Tennessee]], No. 4501 took a few coaches for a complete round trip, turning around at [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/> Afterwards, No. 611 and No. 1218 completed the rest of the trip to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\" />\n\nAt the end of the 1991 season, No. 1218 returned to Irondale, Alabama for an extensive overhaul to have its flues replaced and the firebox repaired.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/> The plan was to have the 1218 running again would be the start of the 1996 operating season, but Norfolk Southern chairman [[David R. Goode]] cancelled the steam program in 1994 due to serious safety concerns, rising insurance costs, the expense of maintaining steam locomotives, a yard switching accident with nine passenger cars in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], and decreasing rail network availability.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/><ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp102-109\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=102-109}}.</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Rail Service - Popular steam engines will take last journeys| first=Don| last=Phillips| newspaper=Indianapolis Star| location=Indianapolis, IN| date=November 6, 1994| edition=first| page=192| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549501/end_of_ns_steam_program_announced/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author=Associated Press| title=Norfolk Southern ends excursions| newspaper=Daily Press| location=Newport News, VA| date=October 30, 1994| edition=main| page=22| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549572/ap_ns_ends_steam_program/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Norfolk Southern steam program was concluded, the 1218 was partially reassembled and towed back to Roanoke to be stored at the East End Shops in 1996, the year its overhaul was supposed to be completed.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp102-109\"/> In 2001, the Norfolk Southern donated the 1218 to the City of Roanoke,<ref>{{cite news| title=Roanoke chugs away on museum honoring locomotive photographer| author=Associated Press| newspaper=Daily Press| location=Newport News, VA| edition=main| date=August 18, 2001| page=24| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549650/daily_press/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> clearing the way for the engine to once again be put on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]].  In June 2003, the museum completed its new Claytor Pavilion and along with it, the 1218 was ready to put back on display.  After a cosmetic restoration by Norfolk Southern, the 1218 was towed to the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] on June 11, 2003, and pushed into place in its new home next to [[Norfolk & Western 611]].  On April 2, 2012, the City of Roanoke officially donated both the 1218 & 611 to the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]].\n\n==Current status==\n[[File:Norfolk and Western Steam.jpg|thumb|right|N&W 1218 on display at the Virginia Museum of Transportation. To the right are N&W Class G-1 #6, N&W Y6A-Class [[Norfolk & Western 2156|#2156]], and [[Pennsylvania Railroad|PRR]] [[PRR GG1|GG1]] #4919.]]\nToday, 1218 is owned by the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in Roanoke, Virginia, and is displayed along with N&W 2156, a Y6a Class 2-8-8-2, (on loan from the [[Museum of Transportation|National Transportation Museum]] in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]]) where they are the star attractions in the museum's Claytor Pavilion.  1218 has been cosmetically restored, though not operational since the overhaul started in 1992 was never completed.  Although the undertaking would be considerable, fans believe it to be capable of being returned to operation, with the incomplete boiler and firebox repairs being the primary scope of work remaining from the aborted overhaul. In 2007, Norfolk Southern pulled the 1218 and 611 to its [[Roanoke Shops]] for the shops' 125th Anniversary celebration.<ref>{{cite book| title=Roanoke Locomotive Shops and the Norfolk & Western Railroad| first=Wayne| last=McKinney| page=116| series=Images of Rail| publisher=Arcadia Publications| year=2014| isbn=978-1-4671-2111-8| location=Charleston, SC| lccn=2013946232| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0appBgAAQBAJ| via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nN&W Class J 611 resides at the Museum when it is not running excursions or at the [[North Carolina Transportation Museum|NC Transportation Museum]] in Spencer, NC, where it was restored to operating condition in 2015. The Virginia Transportation Museum owns the 611 and operates the excursions as Norfolk Southern no longer operates a steam program, though they continue to recognize the excellent corporate public relations that derive from the excursions and have been very cooperative in coordinating such trips. In the meantime, N&W 1218 continues to sit on display inside a shed, next to two other former N&W steam locomotives: the G-1 #6 and the [[Norfolk and Western 2156|Y6a 2156]], the latter which is on loan from the [[Museum of Transportation]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] until 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Trains|Virginia}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation |last=Wrinn |first=Jim |year=2000 |title=Steam's Camelot: Southern and Norfolk Southern Excursions in Color |edition=1st |publisher=TLC Publishing |isbn=1-883089-56-5 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=King|first=Ed|year=2009|title=The A: Norfolk and Western's Mercedes of Steam|edition=2nd|publisher=N&W Historical Society|isbn=978-0970479464|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Rosenburg|first1=Ron|last2=Archer|first2=Eric H.|year=1973|title=Norfolk & Western Steam (The Last 25 Years)|edition=1st|publisher=Quadrant Press Inc.|isbn=0-915276-00-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vmt.org/collections/rail/steam-locomotives/norfolk-and-western-class-a-steam-locomotive-1218/ Norfolk and Western Class A #1218] ''Virginia Museum of Transportation''\n* [http://www.retroweb.com/1218.html The N&W 1218 Image & Video Gallery] ''RetroWeb''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norfolk And Western 1218}}\n[[Category:Preserved steam locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:2-6-6-4 locomotives]]\n[[Category:Simple articulated locomotives]]\n[[Category:Individual locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:Norfolk and Western Railway locomotives|1218]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category: Freight locomotives]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Preserved N&W class A locomotive}}\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name = Norfolk & Western No. 1218\n| powertype = Steam\n| image   = N&W 1218 Brocton, OH on August 6, 1988 (22541514277).jpg\n| caption = 1218 leads an excursion train at Brocton, Ohio, on August 6, 1988\n| builder = [[Norfolk & Western Railway|N&W's]] [[Roanoke Shops]]\n| serialnumber     = 340\n| builddate        = June 1943\n| whytetype        = [[2-6-6-4]]\n| uicclass         = (1\u2032C)C2\u2032 h4\n| gauge            = {{track gauge|ussg}}\n| leadingdiameter  = {{convert|33|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| driverdiameter   = {{convert|70|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| trailingdiameter = {{convert|42|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length           = {{convert|121|ft|9+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}} including tender<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| width            = {{convert|11|ft|2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| height           = {{convert|16|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| axleload         = {{convert|72000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| weightondrivers  = {{convert|433350|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| locoweight       = {{convert|573000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| locotenderweight = {{convert|951600|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| fueltype         = [[Coal]]\n| fuelcap          = {{convert|60000|lb|t|1|abbr=in}}\n| watercap         = {{convert|22000|USgal|abbr=on}}\n| boilerpressure   = {{convert|300|lbf/in2|MPa|2|abbr=on}}\n| firearea         = {{convert|122|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| fireboxarea      = {{convert|587|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| tubesandflues    = {{convert|6052|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| superheaterarea  = {{convert|2703|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}\n| cylindercount    = Four, simple articulated\n| cylindersize     = {{convert|24|x|30|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| valvegear        = [[Baker valve gear|Baker]]\n| valvetype        = Piston valves\n| maxspeed         = 70+ mph<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| poweroutput      = {{convert|5400|hp|abbr=on}}\n| tractiveeffort   = Starting: {{convert|125897|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on}} Continuous: {{convert|114000|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on}}<ref name=GaffneyLeader>{{cite news| title=All Aboard - Steam locomotive to power day-long excursions from Greenville| newspaper=Gaffney Leader| location=Gaffney, SC| date=March 20, 1987| page=7| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549054/the_gaffney_ledger/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n| factorofadhesion = 3.44\n| operator         = [[Norfolk & Western Railway]]\u2192[[Norfolk Southern]]\n| operatorclass    = [[Norfolk and Western Railway class A|A]]\n| numinclass       = 19 of 43\n| locale           = [[United States]], [[Southern United States|South]] and [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]]\n| retiredate       = 1959 <small>(revenue)</small><ref name=GaffneyLeader /><br>1991 <small>(excursion)</small>\n| restoredate      = April 1987<ref name=GaffneyLeader />\n| currentowner     = [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]]\n| disposition      = On static display, based in [[Roanoke, Virginia]]\n}}\n'''Norfolk and Western No. 1218''' is a four-cylinder simple articulated [[steam locomotive]] with a [[2-6-6-4]] ([[Whyte notation|Whyte system]]) wheel arrangement. The [[Norfolk & Western Railway]] built it in 1943 at its [[Roanoke Shops]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]], and was part of the Norfolk & Western's class A fleet of fast freight locomotives.<ref>{{cite news| title=Travel Talk| newspaper=Muncie Evening Press| location=Muncie, IN| date=August 13, 1987| page=26| first=Ellen| last=Ball| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23548921/muncie_evening_press/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> It was retired from regular revenue service in 1959, it was later restored by [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] and operated it in [[Excursion train|excursion service]] from 1987 to 1991. Today it is on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n\n==Historic significance== \nNo. 1218 is the sole survivor of the [[Norfolk and Western Railway|Norfolk and Western]]'s class A locomotives, and the only surviving 2-6-6-4 steam locomotive in the world.  While smaller than Union Pacific's famous and more numerous \"[[4-6-6-4|Challenger]]\" Class of 4-6-6-4 locomotives, Norfolk and Western's design racked up unmatched records of performance in service.\n\nDuring 1218's excursion career, it was the most powerful operational steam locomotive in the world,<ref>{{cite news| title=Mighty locomotive will steam to Fort Wayne| newspaper=Battle Creek Enquirer| location=Battle Creek, MI| date=June 24, 1990| page=20| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23548823/battle_creek_enquirer/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> with a [[tractive effort]] of {{convert|125,897|lbf|kN|2|lk=on}}, well above [[Union Pacific 3985]], the next-strongest-pulling operational steam locomotive, with a tractive effort of {{convert|97350|lbf|kN|1|abbr=on|disp=sqbr}}). Since May 2019, however, No. 1218 became the locomotive with the second highest tractive effort, after [[Union Pacific 4014]], which has a reactive effort of {{convert|135375|lbf|kN|abbr=on}}. Unlike diesel-electric locomotives of similar high tractive effort (for starting heavy trains) but typical for a steam locomotive, it could easily run at 70 miles per hour (113&nbsp;km/h) and more.\n\n==Operational history==\nNorfolk and Western used No. 1218 and the other class A locomotives primarily for fast freight trains, but they also pulled heavy coal trains on the flatter districts of the Norfolk & Western system, and reportedly even pulled heavy passenger trains at times.\n\nIn 1959, when the 1218 was retired, it was purchased by the [[Union Carbide|Union Carbide Co.]] in [[Charleston, West Virginia]], where it was used as a stationary boiler at a chemical plant.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=73-74}}.</ref> In 1965, No. 1218 was repurchased by [[New England]] millionaire [[F. Nelson Blount]] for his locomotive collection at [[Steamtown, U.S.A.]] in [[Bellows Falls, Vermont]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> Three years later, its former owner Norfolk & Western did a cosmetic restoration on 1218 at their East End Shops in [[Roanoke, Virginia]] (the same place where it was built).<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> After that, it was put on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation|Roanoke Transportation Museum]] in 1971.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/>\n\n[[File:N&W 1218, north of Marion, Ohio on August 16, 1987 (22166418064).jpg|thumb|left|Norfolk and Western Railway 1218 in excursion service in 1987]]\n\nIn 1982, the Norfolk & Western and the Southern Railway were both merged to form the new [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] (NS).<ref name=\"Wrinn2000p61\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|p=61}}.</ref> On May 10, 1985, No. 1218 was moved out of the park by a pair of NS diesels to be overhauled at the Irondale Steam Shop in [[Irondale, Alabama]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp73-74\"/> In 1987, No. 1218 was moved under its power for the first time in 28 years and operated for main-line excursion service on Norfolk Southern's steam program.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp79-82\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=79-82}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, No. 1218 traveled to [[St. Louis|Saint Louis, Missouri]], where it met up with locomotives [[St. Louis Southwestern 819|St Louis Southwestern 4-8-4 No. 819]], [[St. Louis\u2013San Francisco 1522|St Louis San Francisco 4-8-2 No. 1522]], and [[Union Pacific 844|Union Pacific 4-8-4 No. 844]] to participate in the [[National Railway Historical Society|NRHS]] convention at the former [[Union Station (St. Louis)|Union Station]].\n\nOn November 3, 1991, during Norfolk Southern's 25th Anniversary of their Steam Program, No. 1218 joined [[Southern Railway 4501|Southern Railway MS Class 2-8-2 No. 4501]] and [[Norfolk and Western 611|Norfolk and Western J Class No. 611]] to triple head a 28-car passenger excursion train from Chattanooga to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=90\u201391}}.</ref> At [[Ooltewah, Tennessee]], No. 4501 took a few coaches for a complete round trip, turning around at [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/> Afterwards, No. 611 and No. 1218 completed the rest of the trip to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\" />\n\nAt the end of the 1991 season, No. 1218 returned to Irondale, Alabama for an extensive overhaul to have its flues replaced and the firebox repaired.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/> The plan was to have the 1218 running again would be the start of the 1996 operating season, but Norfolk Southern chairman [[David R. Goode]] cancelled the steam program in 1994 due to serious safety concerns, rising insurance costs, the expense of maintaining steam locomotives, a yard switching accident with nine passenger cars in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], and decreasing rail network availability.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp90-91\"/><ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp102-109\">{{Harvp|Wrinn|2000|pp=102-109}}.</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Rail Service - Popular steam engines will take last journeys| first=Don| last=Phillips| newspaper=Indianapolis Star| location=Indianapolis, IN| date=November 6, 1994| edition=first| page=192| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549501/end_of_ns_steam_program_announced/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author=Associated Press| title=Norfolk Southern ends excursions| newspaper=Daily Press| location=Newport News, VA| date=October 30, 1994| edition=main| page=22| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549572/ap_ns_ends_steam_program/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Norfolk Southern steam program was concluded, the 1218 was partially reassembled and towed back to Roanoke to be stored at the East End Shops in 1996, the year its overhaul was supposed to be completed.<ref name=\"Wrinn2000pp102-109\"/> In 2001, the Norfolk Southern donated the 1218 to the City of Roanoke,<ref>{{cite news| title=Roanoke chugs away on museum honoring locomotive photographer| author=Associated Press| newspaper=Daily Press| location=Newport News, VA| edition=main| date=August 18, 2001| page=24| url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23549650/daily_press/| via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref> clearing the way for the engine to once again be put on display at the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]].  In June 2003, the museum completed its new Claytor Pavilion and along with it, the 1218 was ready to put back on display.  After a cosmetic restoration by Norfolk Southern, the 1218 was towed to the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] on June 11, 2003, and pushed into place in its new home next to [[Norfolk & Western 611]].  On April 2, 2012, the City of Roanoke officially donated both the 1218 & 611 to the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]].\n\n==Current status==\n[[File:Norfolk and Western Steam.jpg|thumb|right|N&W 1218 on display at the Virginia Museum of Transportation. To the right are N&W Class G-1 #6, N&W Y6A-Class [[Norfolk & Western 2156|#2156]], and [[Pennsylvania Railroad|PRR]] [[PRR GG1|GG1]] #4919.]]\nToday, 1218 is owned by the [[Virginia Museum of Transportation]] in Roanoke, Virginia, and is displayed along with N&W 2156, a Y6a Class 2-8-8-2, (on loan from the [[Museum of Transportation|National Transportation Museum]] in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]]) where they are the star attractions in the museum's Claytor Pavilion.  1218 has been cosmetically restored, though not operational since the overhaul started in 1992 was never completed.  Although the undertaking would be considerable, fans believe it to be capable of being returned to operation, with the incomplete boiler and firebox repairs being the primary scope of work remaining from the aborted overhaul. In 2007, Norfolk Southern pulled the 1218 and 611 to its [[Roanoke Shops]] for the shops' 125th Anniversary celebration.<ref>{{cite book| title=Roanoke Locomotive Shops and the Norfolk & Western Railroad| first=Wayne| last=McKinney| page=116| series=Images of Rail| publisher=Arcadia Publications| year=2014| isbn=978-1-4671-2111-8| location=Charleston, SC| lccn=2013946232| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0appBgAAQBAJ| via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nN&W Class J 611 resides at the Museum when it is not running excursions or at the [[North Carolina Transportation Museum|NC Transportation Museum]] in Spencer, NC, where it was restored to operating condition in 2015. The Virginia Transportation Museum owns the 611 and operates the excursions as Norfolk Southern no longer operates a steam program, though they continue to recognize the excellent corporate public relations that derive from the excursions and have been very cooperative in coordinating such trips. In the meantime, N&W 1218 continues to sit on display inside a shed, next to two other former N&W steam locomotives: the G-1 #6 and the [[Norfolk and Western 2156|Y6a 2156]], the latter which is on loan from the [[Museum of Transportation]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] until 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Trains|Virginia}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation |last=Wrinn |first=Jim |year=2000 |title=Steam's Camelot: Southern and Norfolk Southern Excursions in Color |edition=1st |publisher=TLC Publishing |isbn=1-883089-56-5 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=King|first=Ed|year=2009|title=The A: Norfolk and Western's Mercedes of Steam|edition=2nd|publisher=N&W Historical Society|isbn=978-0970479464|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Rosenburg|first1=Ron|last2=Archer|first2=Eric H.|year=1973|title=Norfolk & Western Steam (The Last 25 Years)|edition=1st|publisher=Quadrant Press Inc.|isbn=0-915276-00-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vmt.org/collections/rail/steam-locomotives/norfolk-and-western-class-a-steam-locomotive-1218/ Norfolk and Western Class A #1218] ''Virginia Museum of Transportation''\n* [http://www.retroweb.com/1218.html The N&W 1218 Image & Video Gallery] ''RetroWeb''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norfolk And Western 1218}}\n[[Category:Preserved steam locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:2-6-6-4 locomotives]]\n[[Category:Simple articulated locomotives]]\n[[Category:Individual locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:Norfolk and Western Railway locomotives|1218]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category: Freight locomotives]]\n", "name_user": "Fan Railer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistoric significance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norfolk_and_Western_1218"}
{"title_page": "The Masked Singer (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{About||the current season|The Masked Singer (American season 3)}}\n{{short description|American reality singing competition television show}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name         = The Masked Singer\n| image             = Masked Singer USA Logo.png\n| image_alt         = Title card of ''The Masked Singer''\n| caption           = \n| genre             = [[Reality competition]]<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=Piester|first=Lauren|title=The Secrets of ''The Masked Singer'': Everything We've Learned About TV's Most Mysterious Show|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|date=February 27, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703044452/https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/1019279/the-secrets-of-the-masked-singer-everything-we-ve-learned-about-tv-s-most-mysterious-show|archive-date=July 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| creator            = \n| based_on           = {{based_on|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]}}\n| developer          = [[Craig Plestis]]\n| director           = {{unbulleted list|Alex Rudzinski|Brad Duns}}\n| presenter          = [[Nick Cannon]]\n| starring           = {{unbulleted list|[[Ken Jeong]]|[[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]|[[Nicole Scherzinger]]|[[Robin Thicke]]}}\n| narrated           = \n| composer           = \n| executive_producer = {{unbulleted list|Craig Plestis ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Izzie Pick Ibarra ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1\u2013)|Rosie Seitchik ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)|Nick Cannon ({{abbr|s.|season}} 3\u2013)}}\n| producer           = \n| company            = {{unbulleted list|[[Endemol Shine North America]] ({{abbr|s.|season}} 1)|Fox Alternative Entertainment ({{abbr|s.|season}} 2\u2013)}}\n| distributor        = {{unbulleted list|[[Fox Corporation]]|Propagate Content}}\n| location           = \n| camera             = \n| runtime            = 42\u201385 minutes\n| opentheme          = {{theme_song|\"[[Who Are You (The Who song)|Who Are You]]\"|[[The Who]]}}\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| network            = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| channel            = \n| picture_format     = \n| audio_format       = \n| first_run          = \n| released           = \n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| num_seasons        = 3\n| num_episodes       = 36<!-- as of April 15, 2020 -->\n| list_episodes      = List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes\n| preceded_by        = \n| related            = {{unbulletedlist|''The Masked Singer: After the Mask''|''The Masked Dancer''}}\n| website            = https://www.fox.com/the-masked-singer/\n| production_website = https://www.smartdogmedia.com/the-masked-singer\n}}\n\n'''''The Masked Singer''''' is an American [[Reality competition|reality singing competition]] television series featuring celebrities in head-to-toe costumes and face masks which conceal their identities from other contestants, panelists, and an audience. After they perform a cover of a famous song, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performances and the celebrity with the fewest votes is eliminated from the competition, taking off their mask and revealing their identity. The [[Nick Cannon]]-hosted show was the first version of the ''[[Masked Singer]]'' franchise to air outside of Asia, premiering on January 2, 2019, on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. \n\nThe show employs four permanent panelists\u2014[[Ken Jeong]], [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and [[Robin Thicke]]\u2014to make guesses as to who the celebrities could be after each performance, with a guest panelist often appearing alongside them. They have received mixed reviews from critics, as have the series' format and production value. However, the costumes have attracted praise. They are designed by Marina Toybina and built by a team of two dozen people who incorporate both [[Haute couture|traditional fashion]] elements and innovative solutions into each costume that help the performer sing clearly and move freely on stage. In recognition of the show's costume design, it has won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] and received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination.\n\nExtensive measures are taken by the show's production crew to prevent the identities of the contestants from leaking before an episode airs. The episodes themselves have received high television ratings; during the [[2018\u201319 United States network television schedule|2018\u201319 television season]], the show was the highest rated new series among adults 18\u201349, leading some commentators to consider the show at the forefront of a new reality television era in the United States. It has spawned numerous spin-offs, including an upcoming dance version and a national tour. Subsequent adaptations of the ''Masked Singer'' franchise worldwide have been credited to the show's success, as has an interest in developing other television series centered on costumes. \n\nThe winners of the first and second seasons were [[T-Pain]] and [[Wayne Brady]], respectively. The series is currently in its [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third season]] which premiered as the [[Super Bowl LIV]] [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|lead-out program]] on February 2, 2020. During an interview prior to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Rob Wade, President of Alternative Entertainment and Specials at Fox, confirmed that future seasons of the show are planned.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\">{{cite web|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Fox Entertainment's Rob Wade|url=https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|website=TV Formats|date=April 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416012653/https://worldscreen.com/tvformats/fox-entertainments-rob-wade/|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live|quote=And then ''The Masked Dancer'' is coming up soon. And future cycles of ''The Masked Singer.''}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Masked Singer US Monster Voiceover.ogg|title=Monster voiceover|description=A sample of a typical voiceover in a clue package showing how modulation is used to disguise the actual identity of the performers on the show while they give hints about their backgrounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nA group of [[Celebrity|celebrities]] compete on the show anonymously in costumes over a series of episodes. The specific format of the competition varies by season and episode, but generally, most episodes feature four to six celebrities performing a cover of a famous song, with the audience and panelists voting for their favorite. The celebrity with the fewest votes in that episode is eliminated from the competition and must take off their mask to reveal their identity. This process of elimination continues for a set number of episodes until three contestants remain, and one is declared the winner after they perform again. There is no cash prize for winning, rather, the celebrity wins the \"golden mask trophy.\"<ref name=\"PeopleS3\">{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed for Season 3, to Premiere After 2020 Super Bowl|url=https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220055111/https://people.com/tv/the-masked-singer-renewed-for-season-3/|archive-date=February 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=From the Banana to the Taco, ''The Masked Singer'' Season 3 Costumes Have Been Revealed|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231616/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/masked-singer-season-3-costumes-first-look-photos-1203485426/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince the second season, the series has also featured a \"smackdown\" round in some episodes in which the two competitors with the fewest votes from their first performances sing again with a second vote occurring, and the performer with the fewest votes is then eliminated.<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Keveney|first=Bill|title=''The Masked Singer'': Producers promise trickier clues, bigger names and crazier costumes|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|website=[[USA Today]]|date=September 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310055251/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/09/24/masked-singer-tweaks-rules-for-16-contestant-season-2/2424261001/|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In the third season, the contestants were divided into three subgroups who each performed on three consecutive episodes before returning to the unified performance format afterwards.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|title=''Masked Singer'' Showrunner Promises Big Changes for Season 3, Says Cast is \"Unbelievably Interesting\"|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207084115/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8549443/masked-singer-showrunner-season-3-changes-surprises-interview|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the singing competition, hints to each masked singer's identity are offered during the show and are referred to as a \"clue package\" by the panelists. Such clues may feature cryptic allusions to what the celebrity is known for, or may be more direct references. Pre-taped interviews are also given as hints and feature the celebrities' electronically masked voices. The panelists are given time to speculate the identity of the singer after their performance and are allowed to ask questions or request that the host offer additional clues.<ref name=\"PeopleS3\"/>\n\n==Panelists and host==\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 450\n| total_height\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1   = Ken Jeong March 2015.jpg\n| alt1     = Ken Jeong\n| caption1 = [[Ken Jeong]]\n| image2   = Jenny McCarthy at E3 2006.jpg\n| alt2     = Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg\n| caption2 = [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| image3   = Nicole Scherzinger 2012.jpg\n| alt3     = Nicole Scherzinger\n| caption3 = [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| image4   = Robin Thicke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt4     = Robin Thicke\n| caption4 = [[Robin Thicke]]\n| image5   = Nick Cannon by David Shankbone.jpg\n| alt5     = Nick Cannon\n| caption5 = [[Nick Cannon]] \n}}\n\nSince the first season, the permanent panel has consisted of actor and comedian [[Ken Jeong]], television personality [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]], recording artist [[Nicole Scherzinger]], and singer-songwriter [[Robin Thicke]], with [[Nick Cannon]] hosting the show.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\">{{cite web|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|title=Fox Orders ''Masked Singer'' Reality Series; Nick Cannon to Host|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102132907/https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/fox-masked-singer-reality-series-nick-cannon-1202893337/|archive-date=November 2, 2019|date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThere are often guest panelists that appear as the fifth panelist on the series\u2014occasionally for multiple episodes. In the first season, they were [[Joel McHale]] (episodes 3\u20134), [[J. B. Smoove]] (episode 7), and [[Kenan Thompson]] (episodes 8 and 10). In the second season, they were [[Anthony Anderson]] (episode 6), [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog]] ([[Robert Smigel]]; episode 7), McHale (episodes 8\u20139), and [[T-Pain]] (episode 10). In the third season, the guest panelists included [[Jamie Foxx]] (episode 1), [[Jason Biggs]] (episode 2), [[Leah Remini]] (episode 3), [[Gabriel Iglesias]] (episode 5), T-Pain (episode 6), McHale (episode 8), [[Will Arnett]] (episode 9), and [[Yvette Nicole Brown]] (episode 11), with [[Sharon Osbourne]] set to appear in the twelfth episode,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-313/313A) \"The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2 / After the Mask: The Mother Of All Final Face Offs, Part 2\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> [[Gordon Ramsay]] in the thirteenth,<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-314/314A) \"The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6 / After the Mask: The Battle of The Sixes: The Final 6\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox02/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref> and [[Jeff Dye]] in the fourteenth.<ref>{{cite press release|title=(MS-315/315A) \"A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals / After the Mask: A Quarter Mask Crisis: The Quarter Finals\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20200416fox06/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]}}</ref>\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size:90%; width:30%;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\"| Panelist timeline\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Panelists\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:15%;\"| Seasons\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|1]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|2]]\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|3]]\n|-\n| [[Ken Jeong]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Jenny McCarthy|Jenny McCarthy Wahlberg]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Nicole Scherzinger]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Robin Thicke]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cMain}}\n|-\n| [[Joel McHale]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[J.B. Smoove]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Kenan Thompson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Anthony Anderson]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[Triumph the Comic Insult Dog]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n|-\n| [[T-Pain]]\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jamie Foxx]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jason Biggs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Leah Remini]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gabriel Iglesias]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Will Arnett]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Gordon Ramsay]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|-\n| [[Jeff Dye]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cNone}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{cGuest}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception and development===\n{{quote box|quote=So we're at a restaurant and my back is to the TV. My daughter said Dad, look at this, there's this crazy thing on. I turned around and all the diners were watching the TV screen. I saw a kangaroo in black pleather singing a pop song. At that moment I said, oh my gosh, I love this! It was bizarre. It was flypaper. It was in a foreign language and you didn't know what was going on, and it was still working. I found out that it was a hit format in Korea, it was a hit show in Thailand. And no one had the [U.S.] rights.|source=\u2014Plestis on the creation of ''The Masked Singer''<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\">{{cite magazine|last=Daswani|first=Mansha|title=Craig Plestis|url=https://issuu.com/worldscreen/docs/tv_formats_miptv_2019|page=38|magazine=TV Formats|date=April 2019|via=[[Issuu]]}}</ref>|align=right|width=35em}}\n\n''The Masked Singer'' is based on the popular<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|title=''The Masked Singer'' Boss on Importance of Contestant Secrecy|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706101843/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-contestant-secrecy-hippo-unmasked-1203089606/|archive-date=July 6, 2019|date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> South Korean series ''[[King of Mask Singer]]''. Television producer [[Craig Plestis]] explained that he first discovered the format during a visit to a small [[Studio City, Los Angeles]] Thai restaurant in October 2017.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|title=How ''Masked Singer'' is reviving costume-led formats|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|website=Television Business International|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407120916/https://tbivision.com/2019/04/05/costume-drama/|archive-date=April 7, 2019|date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While waiting for dinner, he observed the other patrons staring at a television while an episode of the [[The Mask Singer (season 3)|third season]] of the [[The Mask Singer (Thai TV series)|Thai version]] of the show was playing. Intrigued, Plestis began to research the series and secured the rights to produce an American adaptation within one week in a deal brokered by his agent, Steve Wohl of [[Paradigm Talent Agency]]. He then called Fox executive Rob Wade on a Friday night to schedule a meeting with him the following Monday and worked to create a showcase during the weekend.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> According to Plestis, Wade was \"scared\" by the show but envisioned its potential. After successfully pitching the show to Wade under the condition that he \"could cast enough [[A-list]] celebrities,\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\">{{cite web|last=Bentley|first=Jean|title=''The Masked Singer'': How the Fox Reality Show Scored Top Talent (and Kept It Secret)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713155810/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/masked-singer-ep-explains-how-his-insane-reality-competition-made-it-air-1171775|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Plestis began developing the series in November.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Peter|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|title=Fox Developing Remake of Asian Talent Competition ''The Masked Singer''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521062138/https://deadline.com/2017/11/fox-remaking-asian-singing-contest-the-masked-singer-1202206986/|archive-date=May 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2018, executive producer Izzie Pick Ibarra became involved with the show to aid in the casting process and \"[[Americanization|Americanize]]\" the format. Rather than follow the South Korean version in which two singers perform in three rounds, with the winner of the final round facing the winner of the previous episode in an attempt to become the new \"Mask King,\" Ibarra opted to air one elimination per night, emphasize the clue packages and guessing component, and have the celebrities wear more extravagant costumes.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> Plestis agreed, wanting to create a [[story arc]] throughout the episodes and\u2014unlike the South Korean series\u2014be able to reuse the costumes.<ref name=\"TVF Apr 2019\"/> The series was officially ordered by Fox in August 2018.<ref name=\"VAR Aug 2\"/>\n\n[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]], the rightsholder of the ''Masked Singer'' format, lacked the ability to produce the series. As a result, the [[The Masked Singer (American season 1)|first season]]  was produced by [[Endemol Shine North America]] due to Plestis' relationship with the studio. For the [[The Masked Singer (American season 2)|second season]], production transitioned to a new in-house studio, Fox Alternative Entertainment, and the show's budget was lowered as a result.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haynes|first=Dade|title=''The Masked Singer'' Renewed For Third Season, Gets Post-Super Bowl Slot On|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830010304/https://deadline.com/2019/05/the-masked-singer-season-3-to-premiere-after-super-bowl-liv-on-fox-1202613462/|archive-date=August 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|title=Fox Launching Unscripted Studio With ''The Masked Singer'' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817034711/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-launching-unscripted-studio-masked-singer-1209087|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Wade said this gave the network further creative control over the series and allowed it to sell merchandise, launch a national tour, and create spin-off show ''The Masked Dancer''.<ref name=\"TBI Apr 6\"/> Since the second and [[The Masked Singer (American season 3)|third seasons]], respectively, Rosie Seitchik and Cannon have also served as executive producers.<ref>{{cite press release|title=All-New Special \"The Masked Singer: Super Sneak Peek\" to Air Sunday, September 15, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/08/28/all-new-special-the-masked-singer-super-sneak-peek-to-air-sunday-september-15-on-fox-94001/20190828fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=''Beat Shazam'' Host Jamie Foxx Touches Down as a Guest Panelist in The Season Three Premiere of ''The Masked Singer'', Following Super Bowl LIV, Sunday, February 2, on Fox|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/07/beat-shazam-host-jamie-foxx-touches-down-as-a-guest-panelist-in-the-season-three-premiere-of-the-masked-singer-following-super-bowl-liv-sunday-february-2-on-fox-703210/20200107fox01/|via=[[The Futon Critic]]||publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=January 7, 2020|archive-url=http://archive.today/XApNp|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIbarra was ecstatic when Cannon agreed to host the show, citing him as her number-one choice for the role because of his personality and experience. Regarding the panelists, she said the production team was less concerned with selecting those with an ability to critique participants' singing abilities than being able to create a comedic tone for the show as one of their goals was to reassure celebrities they would not be ridiculed for choosing to appear. Jeong was the first panelist to be signed on to the series due to his humour and pre-existing knowledge of the South Korean version, followed by McCarthy Wahlberg and Thicke, respectively, due to their enthusiasm regarding the concept, and Scherzinger for her positivity and experience as a singer.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> On March 28, 2019, Osbourne revealed on ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'' she was originally supposed to be signed on as a panelist for the series; those plans fell through after being contractually obligated to appear on ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furdyk|first=Brent|url=https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|title=Sharon Osbourne Shreds Simon Cowell For Firing Her From ''The X Factor'' Because He \"Thought I Was Too Old\"|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|date=March 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152540/https://etcanada.com/news/435743/sharon-osbourne-shreds-simon-cowell-for-firing-her-from-the-x-factor-because-he-thought-i-was-too-old/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIbarra described casting for the series' first season as less difficult than she predicted due to her strategy of sending the possible participants sketches of costumes that might be featured on the series. She said many of the celebrities had emotional reactions when presented with the proposed costumes and that they were excited to use the show to reinvent their [[reputation|public image]]. [[T-Pain]], the winner of the first season, said he was skeptical about the series until he saw the costume choices, citing the opportunity to wear the Monster outfit as his motivation for participating in the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Erin|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|title=''Masked Singer'' winner T-Pain first deemed show \"probably the stupidest thing\" he'd heard|website=[[USA Today]]|date=March 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111040704/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2019/03/22/t-pain-masked-singer-winner-pitch/3244569002/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, [[Wayne Brady]], the winner of the second season, was approached by producers to appear in the first season but turned them down after being confused about the show's concept.<ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\">{{cite web|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|title=''The Masked Singer'' Winner Interview: \"It's the First Time in My Life I Kept a Secret Months on End\"|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110134353/https://variety.com/2019/tv/features/the-masked-singer-winner-interview-wayne-brady-the-fox-season-2-1203447936/|archive-date=January 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Those who are not professional singers send the show's production crew clips of them singing as a quasi-audition before participating in the series.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/>\n\n===Security===\n[[File:Masked Singer Dont Talk to Me.png|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|While on set, the participants wear an oversized sweatshirt with the words \"don't talk to me!\" on the front to keep their identities a secret.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/>]]\nBefore each of the competitors is unmasked, the show's staff undertakes significant security measures to prevent the participants' identities from leaking, many of which, according to Plestis, originate from his visits to the sets of the South Korean and Thai versions of the show.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As a result, he says the series has two [[bible (screenwriting)|bibles]]: one related to the format and a second, larger one for security measures.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Everyone involved in the series signs a [[non-disclosure agreement]] which prevents them from discussing any revealing information about the outcome of an episode with anyone until it airs on television. After the celebrities have been confirmed to appear on the show, they are allowed to inform a few others who also sign one.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VAR Dec 18\"/> Before arriving on the show's set, the participants and their family, friends, and agents are disguised and driven from a neutral location.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> The manager of [[Joey Fatone]], the Rabbit in the first season, said he was picked up at a [[7-Eleven]] near Television City, given a disguise, and then driven inside the gate.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> Likewise, [[Adrienne Bailon]], the Flamingo in the second season, said she was taken to the set inside of an unmarked black car and only discussed her involvement on the show with producers in a \"secret warehouse.\"<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/>\n\nThe series' security team is almost as large as the production crew.<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> The set has different access levels<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> and each participant is escorted by security guards while disguised with a mask, visor, gloves, oversized sweatshirt, and pants to prevent their skin from showing.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\"/> They are not allowed to talk to anyone except those who wear a special \"stealth cloth\" on their backs.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> Twenty-five people knew the actual identities of the contestants during the first season,<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> though they never referred to them as such on set, in emails, or during phone calls regarding the show (a secret code is used instead).<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/> The participants' names are not listed anywhere on the set, and the crew is discouraged from using their phones for any reason during filming.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> [[Margaret Cho]], the Poodle in the first season, said she never encountered another participant due to the performers' rehearsals occurring at varying times and locations.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/>\n\n===Costumes===\n[[File:Marina Toybina.png|thumb|upright=0.8|alt=refer to caption|The costumes for the series are designed by Marina Toybina.]]\nPlestis described the series' costumes as \"extremely critical\" to the show, adding \"so much money\" is invested in them.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Villareal|first=Yvonne|title=''The Masked Singer'' costume designer takes us inside TV's most colorful closet|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-masked-singer-fox-costumes-marina-toybina-20190206-story.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  They are designed by [[Emmy Award]]-winner Marina Toybina who, using a variety of inspirations, develops the concepts herself. She begins by sketching each costume idea with a pencil and then gives the drawings to one of her friends who creates a digital version. After the costume concepts are shared with the show's producers and Fox executives who decide which designs will be featured during a season, Toybina buys all of the necessary fabrics herself and collaborates with a team of twenty to thirty people to custom-make them.<ref name=\"DH Costume\">{{cite web|last=Grobar|first=Matt|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Marina Toybina Crafted 12 Full-Body Art Pieces In Under Two Months|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913182757/https://deadline.com/2019/08/the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina-emmys-fox-interview-1202660891/|archive-date=September 13, 2019|date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nEach costume costs thousands of dollars to make over two months and the masks are designed to prevent echoes.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/><ref name=\"TBI Apr 5\"/><ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> Beginning as a wire mesh; foam is gradually added around the mask, creating an easy-to-wear helmet shape for the performer.<ref name=\"TC Mar 1\">{{cite web|last=Spellings|first=Sarah|title=How Heavy Were Those ''The Masked Singer'' Masks, Anyway?|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#The Cut|The Cut]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328233201/https://www.thecut.com/2019/03/interview-the-masked-singer-costume-designer-marina-toybina.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AVC\">{{cite web|title=How ''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s costume designer dreams up the show's insane outfits|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eShX30efZd8|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 29, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Toybina says she purposely uses foam for the costumes instead of wood or metal as their heavy weight would make the costumes difficult to move around in.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> As \"the draping and the handwork [for the costumes are] all done the old school way,\" she cites fashion designers [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Thierry Mugler]], and [[Hussein Chalayan]] as inspirations<ref name=\"HP Costume\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Priscilla|title=The Maniacal Costume Designer Behind ''The Masked Singer'' Speaks|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|url-status=live|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915172544/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/costume-designer-masked-singer-marina-toybina_n_5c4f3992e4b0f43e41099257|archive-date=September 15, 2019|date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\">{{cite web|last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Meet the ''Masked Singer'' Costume Designer Behind Those Elaborate Looks|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222072254/https://variety.com/2019/artisans/production/masked-singer-costume-designer-1203103034/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VF Costume\">{{cite magazine|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=January 23, 2019|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Dreamed Up Those Delightfully Delirious Costumes|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|url-status=live|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915040813/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/the-masked-singer-costumes-designer-marina-toybina|archive-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> and says the majority of costumes turn out identical to her sketches.<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> \n\nToybina meets in person with each contestant to choose which costume they want to wear on the show.<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/><ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Due to time constraints, a maximum of two fittings are conducted with each celebrity at a \"very, very private hidden-away\" location<ref name=\"VAR Jan 10\"/> (either the costume shop or Toybina's personal studio)<ref name=\"VF Costume\"/> in which the costumes are tested with a vocal coach present to be sure the celebrities can sing and hear clearly.<ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=Jim|title=''The Masked Singer'' Season 2 Disguises by the Numbers|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|website=TV Insider|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928183052/https://www.tvinsider.com/810949/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes-preview/|archive-date=September 28, 2019|date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"VUL Sep 25\">{{cite web|last=McHenry|first=Jackson|title=''The Masked Singer''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Costume Designer Breaks Down All 16 Egg-cellent New Looks|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221030001/https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/the-masked-singer-season-2-costumes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During filming, the participants are assisted by a production crew that helps them take their costumes on and off.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]], the Butterfly in the second season, said this process was short for her (taking about ten minutes) because the costume she wore was made of only three components.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\">{{cite web|last=Seemayer|first=Zach|title=Michelle Williams Dishes on Getting Electrocuted on ''The Masked Singer'' Set (Exclusive)|url=https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|date=December 12, 2019|website=[[E!#E! Online|E!]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408224246/https://www.etonline.com/michelle-williams-dishes-on-getting-electrocuted-on-the-masked-singer-set-exclusive-137915|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Ibarra, the costumes make it difficult for the contestants to get on and off the stage and their vision is limited when performing on it.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/> [[Tommy Chong]], the Pineapple in the first season, said he \"had to be led everywhere\" because of his difficulty seeing.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> As there are no backups, each costume is sanitized and repaired if needed between episodes.<ref name=\"HP Costume\"/><ref name=\"TVI Sep 24\"/>\n\nFor their work on the first season's finale, Toybina and costume supervisor Grainne O'Sullivan received a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming|Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming]].<ref name=\"Emmy 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|title=Outstanding Costumes for a Variety, Nonfiction, or Reality Programming Nominees/Winners 2019|website=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205042123/https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2019/outstanding-costumes-for-a-variety-program-or-a-special|archive-date=December 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the second season, Toybina won a [[Costume Designers Guild#Costume Designers Guild Awards|Costume Designers Guild Award]] in the Excellence in Variety, Reality-Competition, Live Television category in recognition of her work on the final episode.<ref name=\"CAG 2020\">{{cite web|title=22nd Costume Designers Guild Awards Winners & Nominees|url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|website=[[Costume Designers Guild]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071147/https://costumedesignersguild.com/awards/awards-2019-2020/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:CBS TelevisionCity02.jpg|thumb|left|alt=refer to caption|The series is filmed at [[Television City]] studios in Los Angeles.]]\nThe series is filmed at [[Television City]] in Los Angeles, California, in a studio that seats 380 people.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Kayla|title=Going to a ''Masked Singer'' Taping Is Like Visiting a Top-Secret CIA Compound|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|website=[[Good Housekeeping]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081745/https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/a30677487/masked-singer-season-3-taping-experience/|archive-date=April 5, 2020|date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first season was filmed from June 4, 2018, to June 28, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526204614/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=May 26, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> the second\u2014which introduced an updated set, including a new digital floor<ref name=\"USA Sep 24\"/>\u2014from July 1, 2019, to August 19, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714070242/http://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=July 14, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the third from December 19, 2019, to February 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Masked Singer|url=https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|website=On Camera Audiences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228120213/https://on-camera-audiences.com/shows/The_Masked_Singer|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite the show having a much shorter filming schedule than most television shows,<ref name=\"VOX Feb 27\">{{cite web|last=VanDerWerff|first=Emily Todd|title=''The Masked Singer'' is one of TV's oddest shows. Here's how it was made.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402114050/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/2/27/18241269/masked-singer-interview-finale-recap-preview|archive-date=April 2, 2019|date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> filming dates are occasionally moved to accommodate celebrities' other activities.<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Before the performances begin, several vocal coaches work with the performers for multiple days to determine their strengths and improve their technique.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\">{{cite web|last=Rice|first=Lynette|title=The Ice Cream speaks! Here's how ''The Masked Singer'' recruited the mysterious celebrity|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211102409/https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/26/the-masked-singer-ice-cream-tyler-ninja-blevins/|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Selecting which songs the celebrities sing is a collaborative process, Ibarra says, with both the performers and producers submitting \"ideas [which] merge as [the songs] go through the [[authorization|clearance]] process.\"<ref name=\"BB Jan 31\"/> [[Ninja (gamer)|Tyler \"Ninja\" Blevins]], the Ice Cream in the second season, said he \"definitely got to pick the songs,\" but that the producers want them to be [[mainstream]] so the show's viewers would connect to them.<ref name=\"EW Sep 26\"/>\n\nAt the start of filming, the studio audience is seated next to the stage and a [[warm-up comedian]] tells jokes to loosen them up. They are then encouraged to scream loudly and chant the names of the costumes enthusiastically while the production crew films their reactions for later use. Shortly thereafter, the panelists arrive and the host introduces the first contestant. A clue package plays on the large screen in the studio, and the panelists may choose to write down observations.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/> According to Plestis, the contestants sing live and their voices remain unedited in [[post-production]].<ref name=\"VAR Jan 2\"/> Thicke noted that guessing is a challenge for the panelists due to sound issues in the studio often obscuring performers' voices and that it takes multiple performances for them to catch on to who the celebrity might be. Plestis said the panelists' guesses are heavily edited due to their extensiveness and that they are forbidden from [[Google (verb)|googling]] possible answers to the clues presented to them between the filming of episodes.<ref name=\"E! Feb 27\"/><ref name=\"ADW Feb 6\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Jason|title=How ''The Masked Singer'' Became Broadcast's Biggest Midseason Hit|url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|website=[[Adweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513171046/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/how-the-masked-singer-became-broadcasts-biggest-midseason-hit/|archive-date=May 13, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After the guessing concludes, the panelists and audience vote for their favorite performance using electronic keypads. Their votes are then combined and the contestant with the least amount of votes is eliminated.<ref name=\"GD Apr 5\">{{cite web|last=Dixon|first=Marcus James|title=How to vote for ''The Masked Singer'': Voting process explained (Sorry, there's no app for that)|url=https://www.goldderby.com/feature/the-masked-singer-how-to-vote-voting-app-1203408226/|website=[[Gold Derby]]|archive-url=http://archive.today/tHocx|archive-date=April 17, 2020|date=April 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Before the participant takes off their mask, the producers film the entire studio audience acting out how they would react to the moment, with only a select twenty \"extremely well-vetted\" people remaining in the audience during the actual reveal.<ref name=\"GH Feb 6\"/><ref name=\"THR Jan 2\"/> Before it occurs, the celebrity is allowed to go backstage to fix their hair and makeup.<ref name=\"EW Jan 1\">{{cite web|last=Longo|first=Joseph|title=What we saw at a live taping of Fox's The Masked Singer|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102113745/https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/01/what-we-saw-live-taping-masked-singer/|archive-date=January 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMultiple air-conditioned rooms are located next to the stage which allow contestants to cool down after performing to prevent them from overheating in their costumes. However, mishaps occasionally occur. Toybina said she had to \"reach for the wire and glue\" after the horn of the Unicorn detached during a performance in the first season.<ref name=\"LA Feb 6\"/> While singing during a rehearsal the following season, Williams said she was almost [[electrocution|electrocuted]] after a [[fog machine|smoke machine]] malfunctioned and split in half the boot she was wearing.<ref name=\"E! Dec 12\"/>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{Main|List of The Masked Singer (American TV series) episodes}}\nThe series is broadcast by Fox in the United States and has been [[simulcast]] by [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] in Canada since the second season. The show is available for streaming in the United States on Fox's website and [[Hulu]], and in Canada on CTV's website.<ref>{{cite press release|title= CTV Unveils 2019/20 Primetime Schedule, Featuring Dynamic Dramas with Big Stars and Big Stories|url=https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|publisher=[[Bell Media]]|date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607044629/https://www.bellmedia.ca/the-lede/press/ctv-unveils-2019-20-primetime-schedule-featuring-dynamic-dramas-with-big-stars-and-big-stories/|archive-date=June 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer''|url=https://www.hulu.com/series/the-masked-singer-15209f88-6004-4d73-b993-3ff1a244f494|publisher=[[Hulu]]}}</ref> [[Fox Corporation]] distributes the series in the United States and Canada while Propagate Content does so elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Fox Partners With Propagate Content to Distribute Unscripted Programming |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 7, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017154840/https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/fox-propagate-content-mipcom-1203372433/|archive-date=October 17, 2019|date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Aside from double-length episodes, most run for about 43 minutes and carry a TV-PG or TV-14 [[TV Parental Guidelines|parental rating]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch ''The Masked Singer'': Season 3, Episode 8 \"Old Friends, New Clues: Group C Championships\" Online|url=https://www.fox.com/watch/c2f238d84b5863a804a5455cfc687c05/|website=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Series overview\n| auxA        = Celebrities\n| infoA       = Winner\n| infoB       = Runner-up\n| infoC       = Third place\n\n| color1      = #375D71\n| link1       = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| auxA1       = 12\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| end1        = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| infoA1      = [[T-Pain]]<br /><small>as \"Monster\"</small>\n| infoB1      = [[Donny Osmond]]<br /><small>as \"Peacock\"</small>\n| infoC1      = [[Gladys Knight]]<br /><small>as \"Bee\"</small>\n\n| color2      = #A8957F\n| link2       = The Masked Singer (American season 2)\n| auxA2       = 16\n| episodes2   = 13\n| start2      = {{Start date|2019|9|25}}\n| end2        = {{End date|2019|12|18}}\n| infoA2      = [[Wayne Brady]]<br /><small>as \"Fox\"</small>\n| infoB2      = [[Chris Daughtry]]<br /><small>as \"Rottweiler\"</small>\n| infoC2      = [[Adrienne Bailon]]<br /><small>as \"Flamingo\"</small>\n\n| color3      = #453842\n| link3       = The Masked Singer (American season 3)\n| auxA3       = 18\n| episodes3   = \n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|2|2}}\n| end3        = {{End date|2020|5|20}}<ref name=\"The Futon Critic\"/>\n| infoA3      = \n| infoB3      = \n| infoC3      = \n}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Viewership and ratings===\n<noinclude>\n{{Television season ratings\n| width            = 99\n\n| link1            = The Masked Singer (American season 1)\n| timeslot1        = Wednesday 9:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| episodes1        = 10\n| start1           = {{Start date|2019|1|2}}\n| startrating1     = 9.37<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: ''The Masked Singer'' on Fox Scores TV's Highest-Rated Unscripted Series Launch in Seven Years|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=January 4, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323022456/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-the-masked-singer-on-fox-scores-tvs-highest-rated-unscripted-series-launch-in-seven-years/|archive-date=March 23, 2019}}</ref>\n| end1             = {{End date|2019|2|27}}\n| endrating1       = 11.48<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403155952/https://programminginsider.com/wednesday-final-ratings-michael-cohen-hearing-draws-significant-audience-figures-in-daytime-across-various-networks/|title=Wednesday Final Ratings: Michael Cohen Hearing Draws Significant Audience Figures in Daytime Across Various Networks|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=February 28, 2019|website=Programming Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.a